Professor Watson is a super funny old man. Easy to understand and he cares about his students immensely. Tough on grammar but easy on content. Overall a great class and I will take SPN22 with him

I feel like he is probably better for upper level classes. He is really laid back. Two grades on all compositions, content is grammar. Tough on grammar, content grade is always an A. He does interrupt, but only when you have made a mistake, which is a good thing. Super chill. No accent, super easy to understand.

Yes he interrupts, but you get used to it. I really, really liked Watson. Moves a lot of deadlines back, which was nice. Very good about explaining the readings, which are confusing. Best part was that he made us do almost none of the busy work on the syllabus. It's awesome having a Spanish class where you don't spend hours doing dumb exercises.

Interrupts, and it was to the point of being rude. Don't be a teacher if you're not patient, people are trying and get discouraged--let them figure it out for themselves. I say this as someone who was not often interrupted. Could also be rude in general; I was afraid of him, but I agree with comment that it's easy to become a favorite.

relatively easy grader. does interrupt often, but it's not unbearable. has a weird sense of humor that needs getting used to. but classes went by pretty quickly and he's a good teacher. sometimes scary, though, so watch out - he doesn't like it when people don't participate...
I found the class pretty boring, but he is nice. Not very hard, but I don' think I learned much.
very nice teacher and you learn a lot and the class is interesting.  only downside is he's a hard grader when it comes to grammar.

I think Professor Watson is a really good teacher, and his class does not require a lot of work.  He is a fair grader, too.  Make sure you talk a lot, though, and prepare to be interrupted.  However, his interruptions are not rude--he just wants to help you out.

I totally disagree with Watson's bad ratings. He is a great teacher. I'm going on my 3rd semester with him, and he is always very comical and helpful. Definitely a good professor to have during your time at Tufts!
Absolutely horrible. Run away as fast as you can. He won't let you make a complete sentence and always interrupts. Also is no help if you go to him after school.

I enjoy Watson alot. He has a good sense of humor, and is very helpful with understanding difficult readings.Try to get your thoughts out quick, though, before he cuts you off. He is impatient with students who stutter and suck at speaking spanish.No Lie!

Good spanish teacher-sometimes interrupts you when you speak, but you get use to it. He is more than willing to give you help if you need it and cares how you do. Get on his good side-I tend to believe that it is easy to become a favorite. He likes tennis

Prof Watson could get a little snappy at times, but was generally encouraging. It's important for him to feel like his students are making an effort and are engaged in the class- this definitely affects his opinion of students.
bad spanish teacher. interrupts students trying to practice the language.

Professor Shaw has an impressive background in what she teaches. However, her lectures are erratic and class discussion is pretty terrible. She isn't very clear in what she wants in the work you turn in, either. Overall, she isn't very articulate which throws off the lectures.

Professor Shaw is an accomplished scholar in her field, but this does not translate well into her teaching. The curriculum was interesting, but very reading intensive (5, 200+ page books.) More importantly she was not adequately able to use the text efficiently to convey the concepts of anthropology (lens, ethnography, conflict/reconciliation)

Lectures were slow and boring, often interceded with unhelpful group discussions. She takes a long time to process and share ideas, however she is clearly knowledgeable. She is very kind and does encourage group participation, however classes are slow and filled with awkward pauses.

Professor Shaw is very nice, and it's clear that she is very knowledgeable in her field. However, her class had little structure or clarity. Her TA appeared to do most of the work, and lectures were erratic and sometimes dysfunctional. The material was interesting, but she did little to make it engaging. Half the time she didn't show up

Professor Shaw is very nice, but overall a pretty useless professor.  Her lectures are mediocre and most of the class is wasted on "group discussion" that is unhelpful and uninteresting.  Furthermore, she is extremely unclear about assignments and grades arbitrarily and unfairly.

She is an excellent professor and made this class extremely engaging and well-structured. I was never bored and always felt my comments were encouraged and appreciated. She really listens to students' comments and offers constructive and thoughtful feedback.  Anyone interested in Africa and post-conflict development should take this class!!
even though am a rel maj, this was a terrible class. borring. one midterm, final paper. all. usual reading.
Very intelligent, could use some work on teaching.
No Comments

Unclear as to what he is looking for in assignments work. the Final grade is almost entirely based on a business plan that the class has to decide on whether they like or not? It doesn't really matter whether you do the work according to the book, he is the "decider." Very strange grading system, class is ok.

Very easy class, and pretty interesting. Half the grade is based on a final business plan that takes a lot of work. He gives lots of opportunity for extra credit, and wants everyone to understand the material and do well
great teacher! loved the class. two quizzes that are a bit hard if you do not do all of the reading. short response papers for homework. fun class.
Just gave his last lecture today. Always responds to emails and just amazing lectures on physiology and systems. Wish the best to this guy after having taught more than 40 years here.

Yo Harry is the man. I have taken 3 classes with this guy and every time it is an enjoyable experience. He talks fast and can come off as condescending but as long as you realize that he is joking or just really excited about his work, you will find him great. Definitely go to lectures because his tests are literal regurgitation.
Goes on tangents sometimes, but overall very good. Reasonable questions, fair grader.

He puts together "self study" slides in each of his lectures which are super helpful. If you study those slides, you'll be set for the exam. A little bit awkward in such a large lecture setting but I've heard that he's very personable in smaller settings. I really liked him.

About HB: hilarious, can come off as really awkward, but in an endearing way. Super responsive to emails/outside class. About the class: whole grade determined by 3 tests (for each test you choose 10 FRQs among 12-14 to answer)  miss one class? lol good luck. Book not mandatory, but good at clarifying some stuff
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Amazing lectures', 'Accessible outside class']

rComments: Bernheim is one of the best professors I've had at Tufts. His exams were all short answer essay style questions. He is a very fair grader and gives a lot of partial credit. He can come off as harsh and sarcastic, but he truly cares about his students and that they learn the material well. He loves the kidneys and makes fantastic dad jokes.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lecture heavy', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Accessible outside class']

rComments: Explains things really well, good lectures but he shouts a lot which can get a bit annoying.

Definitely the most interesting and best lecturer in Bio 14. He knows the material so well and is able to simplify even the most complex mechanisms in the cardiovascular and renal systems. I am definitely interested in taking more classes with Bernheim in the future!
Great professor. He knows the material backwards and forwards. Very clear, and a great guy as well.

Great professor and an amazing lecturer. One of the few Bio professors that actually cares about his students' understanding of the material. Always speaks clearly, makes fair tests (no "all of the above"/"2 of the above" and is helpful both in and outside class. Would make a great Bio advisor.

Bernheim's a good guy and makes fair tests, but when you give him a microphone for bio 14, he shouts into it. I'm actually regretting not wearing earplugs to class. He says it's to wake you up, but I couldn't hear what he was saying when he shouted and he actually tired me out. Good professor, though.
Professor Bernhein was great. He was what kept bio14 moving, and made up for some of the poor lecturing from other professors.  He was often repetitive, but it was helpful to reinforce the material.

Physio was a great class with lots of material. Be prepared to take a large amount of notes during class while simultaneously digesting the information. Very clear about what he expects you to know for exams just be sure to pay attention and really get engaged with the material. The best professor I've had at Tufts thus far!

Physiology with Bernheim was great; he covers a lot of material, which means that he doesn't have to resort to tricks on the tests. He is extremely fair. Overall, hands-down the best the Tufts bio department has to offer (which isn't saying much, I suppose...)

Great professor! Talks fast but allows you to record the lectures and this is very helpful.  Tests are very fair and straight forward.  They are not easy because the material is not easy, but there are no tricks.  He lets the material itself make the class difficult.  Tests are 10 short answers worth 10 pts each.  gives a lot of partial credit.

He has clear expectations and high-quality test materials.  Dr. Bernheim fully understands his material (unlike some of the intro bio profs).  This can be intimidating to some students.  However, it means that on tests, he can ask "difficult" questions just by using the material taught during lecture without resorting to silly tricks or word games
Excellent professor. Lots of the people say he talks to fast and shows off, but this simply is untrue. He's very clear about what he expects you to know. take his class!
Bernheim is one of the best bio professor that tufts has to offer, his lecture a very interesting. He also has a very interesting sense of humor.

Don't bother buying the textbook because he doesn't lecture from it or test from it.  He talks way too fast and since all you have to study from is your notes this becomes a problem.  I found him condescending although brilliant.  In office hours he is no less condescending and not helpful.  Take this class at your own risk!

He knows that material very well. This becomes a problem in lecture. It seems as if he is using lecture time to show off just how much he knows and how little his students know. He talks extremely fast and gives misinfo, leaving students confused (especially if you have never taken a class like this before). Like the rest of the bio dept...AWFUL!!!
Professor Bernheim is the best professor I have ever had.  He is extremely entertaining in class and knows his material, very well.

Hard but fair. Tests on notes/handouts, not book. Gives out previous test questions for prep. Talks fast and expects you to keep up while scribbling like a madman. Very helpful if you go after it. Good guy.

Professor Bernheim is by far one of the best teachers at Tufts.  Many believe he jumps around, but this isnt true.  He's so interesting and knows so much that he applies what we're learning to different topics and situations.  Many might find that disorganized but rather it portrays the extent of his knowledge.  Tests are hard but fair. Best Prof!
Best science teacher at tufts by far.

Prof. Bernheim was by far one of the most enthusiastic and interesting I've had at Tufts. His tests are difficult and he does expect you to know everything and apply it, but you learn tons. He speaks quickly and jumps around, but if you reread your notes, you get the point. Go to his review sessions, they're very helpful. GREAT PROF!

one word: disorganized. He's a funny guy, and really nice, but he jumps all over the place. It may just be the setup of the course, but I had trouble figuring out what was going on. Instead of saying what he needs to say and moving on, he jumps all around a subject without stating the main idea.

He speaks like a bandit...Who could keep up??  Yes, he is very available if you have a question, but he  is also rather condescending about it.  Oh yeah, and all of a sudden he'll start YELLING random WORDS throughout his LECTURe...its really annoying, especially at 10 in the morning.

He was one of the most unclear and obnoxious professors ever. If you ask a question he is really condescending and not helpfull at all.  He is really disorganized which makes the class super confusing, especially since he expects you to memorize tons of numbers/equations/names.  Avoid this class!
Indeed one of the best professors across the entire university. Teaches challenging material with passion, enthusiasm, and patience. His wit and friendliness are equally outstanding.
Very clear in class, explaining concepts thoroughly.  Also very willing to help outside of class.
prof. bernheim was really good and funny.  the class is tough but he made it interesting.

AWESOME prof! He was also my advisor; I picked him as an advisor because I enjoyed his teaching so much! He does speak fast, but is always available if you have questions. He is extremely enthusiastic which is what a teacher should be.
He loves the topic he teaches and he doesnt want anyone to fail.  Fun class.
Enthusiastic. Has a true passion for this subject.  Talks a bit too fast which makes it difficult to absorb everything that you are required to know.
Bernheim is a smart man and pretty goofy and funny, but he talks wayyyy too fast and is totally disorganized, which is bad for learning complicated psysiology.
wonderful, enthusiastic, one of the best teachers at tufts
No Comments
No Comments

She is an EXTREMELY nice prof, w/ a phd from Harvard, that LOVES the material.  Just read the assignments, make sure you know what she tells you to know.  When it comes to test time, just write what she told you.  One of the most straight forward classes at Tufts.  Read the material, attend each class, take half decent notes and it is an easy A.

She is very nice but very old.  You must follow her explanations of the text for her tests and you should write down anything word in the text that she references or explains.  Her class is fairly easy, but her tests look for strict answers and she does not give double jeopardy.

Merzlak is SO nice.  She is a really sweet old lady.  That said, she is very rigid structurally and alternate interpretations of the text bewilder her.  She doesn't seem to know anything about it other than what is written in our edition of the Metamorphoses.  She knows that REALLY well though.
easy, interesting reading, strict teaching.  don't be late or go to the bathroom during class time.  she will not let you move a quiz or exam unless you're sick.

Boring, and tests require very specific information.  The professor barely enriches the text, so you could read them on your own, and have almost the same intellectual experience without the agonizing boredom.

You will definately brush up on your Latin grammar.    Merzlak seems to be somewhat distant at first, but if you talk to her for a few minutes, totally different story.  Nice lady and knows her Latin.
I have had Merzlak for several courses including Classics of Greece, Latin 22 and her summer course on Ovid.  She is much better in Latin and the Ovid course.  The Ovid course in the summer is great!

If you get to know her, she is really nice and helpful.  Her teaching style is not like the  people in English, but  give her a chance, you can get a lot out of the course. She really wants you to feel the literature. She has published 3 books of poetry!

she's pretty old and kind of boring, but she loves the material, which is pretty much what makes classics of greece bearable. that and the fact that it's incredibly easy if you do the reading and show up to class (most of the idiots in the class don't).
No Comments
He's really rude.

Sergiy can come across as intimidating and harsh, but he is actually very helpful . He knows that Chem 1 and 2 are weedout classes and designs the class as such but gives tons of practice tests and resources to prepare for the super hard tests. Because it's so rewarding and satisfying to do well, Kryatov's class made me really like chemistry.
Assigns loads of busy work that's irrelevant to exams

Clear expectations and plenty of resources for students to succeed. Practice tests and answer keys are posted before every exam including the final. Many think he isn't approachable, but he's perfectly fine in office hours. With that said, lectures were dry (just him reading the slides). The course is a lot of work, but manageable.

Kryatov is a great teacher. His lectures are usually boring and he does read straight off the slides, but if you go to him during office hours he really wants to help you and 100% knows what he's talking about. The people who complain about him are the people who don't do the work he tells you to do. Read the textbook, pay attention during class.
teacherRatingTags: ['Accessible outside class', 'Clear grading criteria', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: After finishing a semester without taking a kryatov course, In hindsight kryatov was such a bad professor. He had incredibly dry lectures, very little concern for his students, and he was bad at teaching. Try to avoid taking chem with this guy because he almost made me quit pre-med. He's also rude if you ask him questions. Bad all around.
if you put in the work, you will do well

Chem1 covers a lot of content, and Kryatov does a good job of getting through all the material in lecture. He also teaches very closely to the textbook, which is nice. However, his explanations in lecture don't go into depth about how/why things work, so I found that I had to read the textbook a lot to fully understand things.

Tough class, but if you're prepared to work you'll do well. Lots of resources: problem sets, recitation problems, he releases 3 past exams before every exam. Lecture can be dry but he knows what he's talking about. Often reads directly from slides but goes more in depth; slides are posted ahead of time so you can take notes before lecture.

Dr. Kryatov is a fantastic professor, but he is not perfect. He is difficult to approach, not due to lack of office hours, because he deals with bad questions badly. He moves quickly and sometimes gives unsatisfying responses. He goes above and beyond for his students; he posts answer keys to tests within 15 minutes of the tests conclusion.
He's a legend!

I have never cried so much from one class. Kryatov covers the very basic material in class and explains it poorly. The material in the homework is completely different and the tests seem like theyre from another course. Expect to spend 6+ focused hours per day on chem work.

One of the most difficult classes I've ever taken. Kryatov explains the material, but many hours of practice are required to have a chance at doing well on exams. Regardless, exams are brutal and although Kryatov is a decent lecturer, he can be downright mean. Definitely a premed weed out class. Beware.

I went to Professor Kryatov several times outside of class, and there he was helpful. But, during lecture, he reads straight from his slides. Tests are challenging. But, the reason why I gave him such a row rating is becasue he was incredibly mean to a few students in my lecture and refused to answer questions he deemed "pointless."

Kryatov is one of my favorite professors at Tufts. Yes, he's hard. His class may be a weed out, but you learn so much. Those that are dismissing him on this forum are probably pre-medical students that struggled in the course who probably shouldn't even be doctors.
A combination of him and the class the lectures have a lot of material. Exams are very challenging but he does post previous exams and practice exams.

Prof Kryatov is a difficult professor who values hard work. intro chemistry is very hard. he is a fair grader, but if you don't put in the time you will not do well in his course. comes off as intimidating but he's a fine guy

Kryatov isn't very approachable Chem1 covers a ridiculous amount of material for an introductory class. His tests are fair, though, and all of his lecture powerpoints are uploaded to Trunk, so missing lecture isn't a big deal.

I stopped showing up to class after the first midterm, since all he does in class is just read the lecture slide available online. You know the professor is not very great when my friend hasn't showed up to class once this semester, but still got a good grade. The kid didn't even know what the professor looked like on the day of finals.

Tough and boring material that is presented with great clarity and organization. Only take this class if you are willing to work hard. The resources to study are readily available, but you will need to be willing to put in lots of hours to do well. Also, labs are rough.

I think the curriculum is what's difficult. Since there is so much packed in there he will often say that he "can't digest the material for you" which is very true. I had to spend lots of time outside of class reviewing. When he has open Q&A sessions before exams it shows how brilliant he is, even if he misunderstands your questions sometimes.

His class was so difficult! I went to tutoring, study group, and I pay attention in class but it makes no sense to me. The class takes up 90% of my workload and it is miserable! I find it extremely difficult, I really think you have to have taken AP Chem in high school to be able to succeed because you need a strong foundation to do well.

Best professor at Tufts -- teaches with a level of detail and thoroughness seldom seen with other professors. Slides for every lecture, multiple practice exams, and curves every exam to an 80. Admittedly can be dry because he is a no BS guy. Those claiming the class is too hard realize they were wrong after taking the remaining pre med reqs.

Sergiy thrives off of crushing the dreams of premeds, even though one-on-one he's okay.  Speeds through lectures and makes his exams KILLER.  Like yea chem is hard but pleasE this is excessive.  But the man is sassy and honestly if you don't have a life outside and sell your soul to the class you'll probably survive.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Tough grader', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: Chemistry 1 and 2 are both incredibly difficult classes but Kryatov does a pretty good job getting all the information to you. Lecture slides are always online and are usually very helpful. The tests are much more difficult than homework/lectures, and there is a lot of homework, both written and online. Lecture is pretty boring though.

Prepare to work hard, but also be prepared to learn a lot. This class is hard, but it gives a strong foundation of chemistry. Lots of work: lectures, labs, online and paper assignments. Tests are hard, but there will always be a perfect bell curve with the middle set perfectly on a 75. Would recommend. Accent, but easy to understand. Accessible.
He's a great professor- super organized and really clear in his lectures but the tests are brutal. You really have to work hard if you wanna do well.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lecture heavy', 'Lots of homework', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: The exams are much harder than the lectures and homework. In addition, they contain lots of detail-specific questions. However, your grade is not weighted heavily by the final or any one exam so if you put in effort throughout the year with lab and homework you'll do fine. It's a lot of work though.

Professor Kryatov is both caring and fair. His practice problem sets and exams are always helpful. There's a lot of material thrown at you, but he understands chemistry well and genuinely wants to see you succeed. He consistently tries to let students out on time and has great demonstrations/short experiments. Attend the many office hours offered.
He is really responsible and his lecture is quite clear. Pay attention to the problems that he gives in class. If you understand the problems in class then most of the homework won't be a problem.
His lectures are clear, but the tests are pretty hard. Go to his office hours.
Great professor. If you didn't do well in the class it was because you didn't try hard enough. He's very fair, straightforward, and will always help if you ask.

Kryatov is a very clear lecturer and as long as one puts in enough effort and energy into studying for the exams they will succeed. In lecture, Kryatov tends to rush through since the course covers a bunch of different topics, but he is always ready to help in office hours.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lots of homework', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Clear grading criteria']

rComments: Professor Kraytov is a very fair grader and test writer. The tests are hard but not impossible. Lectures are very clear and he provides practice tests before the exams which are really helpful.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Lots of homework']

rComments: Kryatov is a clear lecturer but tends to overemphasize minute details and  mumbles important concepts, so its vital that you sit towards the front. There is a lot of work in the course between the problem sets, laboratory and exams, but it is possible to do very well in the course if you put in sufficient time. Overall he is a clear but hard prof
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Lots of homework', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: He aight

There's not a lot of individual attention because it's a big lecture class, but he's always really willing to help when needed and answers student questions fully. He doesn't speak very loud so sitting near the front would help. Also, read the text before getting to class. It makes it a lot easier to understand the material
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', 'Lots of homework', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: Professor Kryatov delivers very clear lectures that contain all the information necessary to doing well on tests.  Assuming that you complete the onlinepaper homework and put some effort into lab reports, the only really challenging part of the class is studying hard enough to do well on the 3 tests and final (count for 70% of your grade).
confusing accent and very hard tests... very hard
Clear lectures, but ramps up the difficulty on the tests, big-time.

Professor Kryatov's a great guy. The material can be challenging, but that definitely is just the nature of the subject. His exams can be tough, but overall they're pretty straightforward, and no questions will be unfair. He's always available also, so if you have any kind of issue, contact him, he'll hear you out. Overall, this is a great class.

Professor Kryatov is a smart teacher who is really engaged in what he's teaching. His dry humor really adds to the lectures which are very long and boring at times, though he does move quickly so it is important to pay attention at all times. His lectures are organized, too. Incredibly helpful one-on-one, even in a class of 300+ students.

The class can be difficult and it has a lot of work, but he's very reasonable.  He's fair with grading and curves each test. He's very accommodating, so if you have a problem or question, definitely go to him - he's a nice guy and will hear you out.  That being said, he's a bit of a monotonous lecturer.  I taught myself a lot of the content.
very hard tests you must know your stuff inside and out! a lot of work

Kryatov makes you kry. haha I'm funny. But really, I didn't any chem knowledge going into Tufts and I came out and knew my stuff. His tests are hard but not impossible- he gives three practice tests before each. Usually one is representative of the real deal and the other two are easier. The keucces here is READ THE PPTS OVER AND OVER!

Prof. Kryatov is pretty dry as far as lecturers go but he covers all of the topics comprehensively and provides all the necessary material you need to get a good grade. As long as you study a week or two before each class and use everything he gives you, you'll do fine. He's also a pretty funny guy on top of all that

Great professor! cares a lot about his students success in the class. He provides Q&A session from his personal time to help the students. I remember once he had one on a school holiday. very dedicated dude

I can't put my finger on it but he did something right. I hated chem in high school and did not do great on the AP but got an A in his class cause I went to all the lectures and paid attention. The exam prep materials he gives are super helpful. A lot of people complain about how hard the class is but it's definitely jut the nature of the subject.

I really like Professor Kryatov and don't think people give him enough credit. Chem 1 is hard enough as it is, and people complain mainly because they aren't willing to do the work. As long as you put in the effort, study hard for about a week prior to each test, and understand this isn't a high school chem class, you really will do fine.

Professor Kryatov is THE MAN. He's so funny, and his lectures are short, to the point, and he always finishes class on time. He provides tons of study materials, from practice tests to recitation sets to book problems. His class is definitely not easy, and I would consider it a weed-out class. But it's interesting, and you can do well if you work!

I'm marking Hot because of his thermodynamics lecture.  Kryatov is one of the most dedicated professors I have ever had.  I'm profoundly impressed by his ability to give clear lectures, immensely fair exams/grading, and dedication to his students.  He's great.

His tests are SUPER hard, but he also prepares you well with the 3 practice exams. If you are willing to spend about 3 days of nonstop studying for each test, you will do fine (he also curves). They recently changed the Chem 2 syllabus to include Organic Chemistry and he rushed through SO MUCH in 2 weeks, it's awful. Besides that, good pacing.

I think if you knew chemistry going into the course you could probably do fine. However he speeds through the powerpoints and its difficult to actually learn chemistry from him. He is a strict grader when it comes to regrades and final grade cutoffs. I found him not to be too helpful during office hours as there often was a cultural divide.

His lectures are very clear and straight forward. He's actually pretty funny at times and makes the whole class laugh, but you gotta be paying attention, its subtle. The tests are decently hard, but not impossible. Its an intro class, and he does a pretty good job of it. Organized and thoughtful and straight to the point.

Kryatov is pretty awesome. Some people find the class challenging, but he gives you plenty of past tests etc. to study from and he is super helpful during office hours. He has a great personality and is a pretty funny guy. I was not expecting to have such a good professor for an intro course.

He can be super funny and has an awesome accent. He is extremely helpful, especially if you take the time to ask questions and go to his office hours. He has way more office hours than most professors; he is dedicated to making sure that you do well. His tests are very specific, though, and focus on small details very often.

he teachers right off the powerpoint he puts online and only once in a while will he add anything to them. He is very clear . He has a unique sense of humor. Basically he'll do something funny and then show no emotion. Not a bad class to take.

His lecture slides are so easy to follow and he teaches the class so clearly, so it is really helpful to go to lecture because he does problem types that show up on the tests and homework. Hard exams, but he's an awesome professor for the subject.

Kryatov is a great teacher. Has all the lectures and lecture notes posted online so if you miss a class, you can catch up. Practice exams perfectly reflect the actual exams in the class. If you're in his 8:30 class, make sure you sit in the front, that way you definitely won't fall asleep (chemistry can be a bit dry)

As a student who had already taken general chemistry and got a 5 on the AP test, the course was still challenging but manageable. Dr. Kryatov is a very thorough professor and wants people to do well in the class. There are always 2 problem sets every week so be prepared.
Dr. Kryatov is unintentionally funny at times. The man really knows his chemistry and he'll definitely make time for you if you need to have a concept clarified. Exams are difficult, but manageable.

Kryatov is THE best. His lectures are always absolutely crystal clear, and the amount of review material he gives you to study from is AMAZING. Although his accent may make him seem a bit intimidating at first, by the end of the semester you'll love him. The class isn't easy, but he does a great job explaining material in a fair, concise way.

Kryatov is a great professor, but I really resent the testing. You really have to memorize every little detail from his lectures, whether it seems important or not. Luckily, it's all online in his lecture slides. But especially since this class is also for non-majors, it still digs at me to have to memorize such unimportant facts.

Great guy, very clear and very nice. If you read the book and his lecture slides, you will do well in this class. Tough class to teach given the amount of people in it but he does it the best of anyone I have seen.
Seems a little scary, but really very nice and concerned with students

I was really intimidated by Kryatov towards the beginning of the semester. I eventually realized that he is pretty concerned with students' understanding and he's an overall excellent professor.  He designs the course really well, so that if you attend lectures and spend adequate time working on problem sets/studying, it is hard not to succeed.

Seems like a good guy. Lectures are very boring -- really you get just as much out of them by printing them out from the internet. Does a good job for it being such a large class. Chem 1 is a little bit difficult but if you do the reading and look at his powerpoints it is impossible to do poorly.

I had Kryatov for Gen Chem 1 & 2. Classes weren't exactly entertaining but he explained the material well. He sometimes does random fun things in class like play with dry ice or set hydrogen balloons on fire.

Professor Krayatov is a quality teacher. He covers a huge amount of material quickly and clearly. He can be a little distant, and don't expect him to learn your name, but he knows how to teach. Chem 1 & 2 are very hard, with a weekly online problem set and weekly paper problem set and weekly labs, but you will know chemistry by the end of it!

Extremely brilliant professor, able to answer any question you may have. Knows how to teach this introductory course in a logical, coherent, and accessible manner. Practice problems are extremely helpful, and puts everything online, with detailed explanations which help for test studying. Lectures are inherently boring, unfortunately.
Good class.  Crystal clear lectures-->he gives you the lecture slides so thats wicked nice.  But if you don't take notes its easy to space out.
Lectures are boring but comprhensive, tests are exactly like the problem sets, this class is just what you would expect from a huge lecture class

The class is a lot of work. You will always be doing something for chemistry. But that being said if you do the work you will do well. Lectures are boring BUT clear. All the info you need is there. You can tell he really loves his subject and he is open to meet with students during office hours.

Very friendly professor, extremely clear. Prints out copies of Powerpoints for everyone and does many practice problems. Has 3 practice tests with answers for exams that are very similar to actual exams and are very helpful.  Loves chemistry and does a lot of exciting demoes that made class much more interesting. Homework was moderate.

Overall, an outstanding professor.  Really understands the material and wants his students to as well.  The practice exams and problem sets will prepare you for the exams, which are difficult but always incredibly fair.  The online problem sets are annoying but a good way to boost your grade.  Overall, great guy.  Go see him outside of class.

Very difficult class and even more difficult to stay awake in the morning lecture. If you're taking this, it's probably because of pre-med, so you just have to push through it. Sergei is very Ukrainian. His lecture notes are extremely helpful and he gives three practice exams with answers before each test.
he's a very honest professor who prepares you well for his exams, which are fair but a bit hard just because it's chemistry. go to lectures! unless you want to memorize the book.

He does very well preparing you for tests. He prints out lecture slides and does a lot of problems out in class. He's very knowledgeable about the class material. Practice tests really help you prepare for the tests. Online problem sets really help your grade and understanding. Paper problem sets, too. Homework is moderate for a science class.

He's soooo sweet. The material was simple but he would do anything to make sure everyone understood. He also scales the exams so everyone gets a better grade. Pace is kinda slow sometimes so it might get a little boring but he's such a good teacher u won't regret taking his class.

He's from the Ukraine and has an accent, but once you get past that, you see that he's a brilliant prof.  The problem and lecture sets prepare you well for his tests.  He's also really nice outside of the classroom.

Psets can get pretty nasty but overall was an easy class. He gives all (or most) the notes and solves practice problems in class. Sometimes seems to pull things out of nowhere, and he might not understand students' questions, but nice when asking for help. Easiness of tests doesn't even compare to prof dewald's.

One of the most boring classes I have ever taken. It doesn't help that the class is at 8:05 in the morning (ONLY section offered both semesters). He plows right on through the material, hardly ever stopping. He rarely asks if there are questions, and doesn't really explain in much detail when there are. The problem sets can be extremely tedious.
It was hard, but he is clear and fair.  A nice guy.
Lots of fun to work with. Loves urea very much.

For Chem 1 and 2: Avoid at all costs as a prof. Goes off on tangents and then puts what he says on the exams even though they aren't related to lecture or the book. Also never available for office hours, which Tufts must hate because they always emphasize how important it is. He can't be bothered with students and their questions and shows it.

He's a good teacher for summer chem, which is a really condensed course for an already-tough subject. If you're worried about the prof for the summer course, don't worry about kenny, he's willing to help and he's a nice guy.
He is nice but awkward. Tests are fair.
Somewhat hard to understand in lecture and slightly awkward outside of it, but just a generally great guy who wants to see his students succeed and is willing to put in the effort to help them.
Not as hard as it could have been, but still Pchem

Professor Kenny is... interesting. Pretty convoluted lectures, read the book and you'll get the same thing. Notes on the book are probably more useful. A difficult class, very mathematical, and difficult problem sets. Tests are hard and poorly worded- but manageable.
His presentation was... lacking. And rather boring. Overall, not a bad professor, just not the greatest.

The class definitely is not as hard as Kenny could make it. His lectures dont really add anything to what's already in the book. Lots of application of math to simple chemical concepts. Tests were 4 questions long, usually half theoretical half computational. Pretty fair class, average was a B I think. Dont cram and youll do well.

This is one of the most useless classes i have ever taken. It is poorly organized, and I learned nothing the entire semester. Plus he makes you write a journal entry for every class for extra busy work. Do not take this unless it is required for your major

NEVER take environmental chem with Kenny. He might mean well, but I have never taken such a poorly organized class--I had to go on wikipedia to find the explanations for our p-sets since he was so useless. If you're looking for a good way to get your science req. out of the way, this isn't it!

he is very interested in the class and his lectures are exactly the same as what he puts online (so if you miss class it is ok) tests are fair. I strongly suggest going to office hours whenever you have a chance.

Hes really excited about this class (P chem) and loves to get sidetracked talking about sciency things (the wright lectures for example). Overall not too bad. Sit in the back row and you will be given mad props from kenny.

his lectures/teaching style were hard to get used to at first but if you need help he is very willing.  he's a nice guy but his material is tough.

This is miserably difficult because no assignment is accepted until everything is correct.  Professor Stolow just keeps giving it back until you get it right.  Tough love, but you will get it right in the real world.

Stolow was definitely the worst professor I've ever had. He was very unreceptive to students' questions, never responded to emails, and his lectures were hard to follow. He would sometimes also quiz us on information unrelated to what we had learned in lab lectures or even in the corresponding organic chemistry class.

Horribly long lectures that did not help in neither the quizzes nor the labs themselves. Everyone was online during each lecture because paying attention wasn't necessary, but attendance was because there was a quiz at the end of each lecture.

I had Stolow for lab lecture and he is a brilliant man but it is EXTREMELY hard to hear him and so its really easy to doze off in his lecture. Nice man very helpful but he is incredibly verbose and technical and monotonous which makes it hard to pay attention. He also stopped posting answer keys to the practice quizzes which wasnt nice.

Before I took Stolow's class, an upperclassman had advised me not to take Orgo with Stolow. I wish I had heeded that advice. Stolow is a HORRIBLE lecturer who DOESN'T TEACH! If you are reading this, my advice would be to take Orgo with anyone else!

Stolow is caring, but he is a horrible professor.  The entire class is on their cell phones during class and he goes through tedious power points.  If he runs out of material, he'll just read the textbook until the end of class.  Additionally, his tests are ridiculously and unnecessarily difficult and the grading is stingy.  Would not recommend
Excellent professor. Stolow's a boss. He's difficult, but you'll learn a lot.
Nice person, slow teaching. Too slow.
Be prepared to teach yourself everything or spend a load of money on a tutor. Do yourself a favor and just take organic with (1) another professor or (2) at another school.

I have learned nothing from Stolow. Everything I understand is because of the book. During his lectures, he spends too much time talking about tiny details, and then won't give you enough time to copy down the important things during the lecture.
A sweet guy. actually wants to teach you but really too old and sometimes forgets things
awful, boring, unable to teach, just reads the textbook, extremely picky grader
Horrible, just reads the textbook in class, does not teach

Awful. Just awful. Worst professor I've ever had. Poor explainer, nit-picky grader, and boring. He occasionally flashes some charm or a bit of a sense of humor, but I would much rather have had someone who could actually teach orgo than occasionally be charming.
Good professor, sometimes is very boring, but if you pay close attention he randomly really funny and entertaining.  Keep up with the work in this class or your screwed.
Really is a terrible professor - go over information sparsely in class and only goes into detail on the exams, and refuses to scale.

Professor Stolow does show concern for his students understanding. He will schedule review sessions way in advance and will try to give studying tips constantly. The problem is...the review sessions are not always helpful. He takes too long on one problem and you may miss doing three other problems because of it. Okay, that would be totally fine if

This professor needs to seriously consider retiring. He's boring and lecture are useless for the most part. He gives you practice exams but won't give you the answers to help you study. NOT HELPFUL! Tests are way harder than practice exams, be warned.
need to seriously consider retirement (i'd say early retirement, but i think we're way past that point)... lab lecture is incredibly boring and not to mention completly pointless

Very Helpful, and very concerned about student's process. He is willing to spend his time (4 hours/week) to organize review sessions for various topics

Keith Maddox is fantastic; he teaches a big class, but if you go to office hours, he's so helpful and really wants to get to know you. Social Psych was interesting with him, and he always tries to make the lectures more interesting with personal stories or demonstrations. Tests are straightforward, and there is one paper, but it's graded fairly.

Professor Maddox was an incredible speaker who clearly cared deeply about his subject area and put an impressive amount of time, effort and personality into each lecture. While the tests were difficult, he made preparation easy and there were only 3. One paper, graded easily. Overall, incredible professor, don't miss out on his classes.

Professor Maddox was an enthusiastic professor who clearly loves what he does. The lectures and activities were pretty interesting. If you study a lot, you'll do fine on tests. That said, the free response questions often cover small topics on slides, so study a lot beforehand. The material was interesting, but to be honest a lot was common sense
I really liked maddox!  He was funny and nice.  his slides were usually very clear, but sometimes sparse and i would miss the main point of them.  overall, i would say he was good!

He's a great professor and all around person. His lectures are funny and informative and he makes sure that everyone has a good grasp of the material by the end of class. His test questions are fair and to the point. All in all, a very good professor
Maddox's lectures are definitely the most engaging. He gives good examples that stick with you, and is clearly passionate about what he teaches.

Maddox is a genuinely caring professor! Class is awesome and so so interesting - so don't miss it, he's a fun guy and a great lecturer. DO YOUR READINGS. Go over the powerpoints a thousand times because he has open response questions, that you're not going to remember answers to without studying. I got an A and I prepared a lot before exams.

UM...KIND OF FANTASTIC!I had prof. maddox for psych 13: social psych. he feeds off energy from the class, so give him somethng to work with to keep it from being another lecture.Notes posted online, he pays attention to detail and if you pay attention to lecture and do the reading, the tests are a breeze. i got a c in the class. my fault, not his.
UM...KIND OF FANTASTIC!

He is a clear, funny, and down-to-earth professor. 5% attendance, 25% written (1 paper, careful! grading is rough on this), 70% tests (40pts MC, 20pts written). Non-cumulative! I never sought help, but he implored us to and he answered questions clearly in class.

This class was almost all student lectures so Prof. Maddox didn't really teach much. When he did he was great. Do wish he was more organized, though. Only got one assignment back throughout the entire semester. Super friendly, easygoing guy.

Keeps lectures interesting and clear, doesn't read off powerpoints but rather uses it as a guide. Cracks jokes occasionally and is a generally nice professor. Midterms are fair and Maddox creates study guides to be clear about what is to be expected on tests.
A great, entertaining guy.  I loved the class, and I highly recommend it.
Great guy. Very chill, and easy to talk with.
entertaining
As an alumnus, I can say that conversations with Dr. Maddox are some of my fondest memories, due to his sincerity, interesting ideas, and concern for students.
He was my advisor, and was always a great, helpful guy to meet with.
interesting class

Professor Jampel is not an engaging teacher; his lectures are long and tedious, and he has a tendency to expound upon random, uninteresting and inapplicable tangents. The textbook is rarely discussed in class, and yet the tests rely heavily upon it. He does not effectively explain concepts or utilize his powerpoints.

Awesome professor! He's really engaging and tells interesting stories in class. I couldn't have gotten through a 3 hour class with any other professor. He really knows his stuff and can offer additional insight from his decades of experience in the field. Jampel is the man!
Is not helpful and assignments are not clear

Great abnormal psych teacher. Clear and has experience, tests were reasonable, grading is reasonable too (i had diff take on one test question and he accepted it). Only problem was the class was @ 830am on fri, but he gave us a 15min break every time. Learned a lot.

Dr. Jampel is a great teacher.  Tells stories from his experiences working in the field to bring the material to life.  Tests are very reasonable, and class is surprisingly interesting, only problem was it was Friday morning.

Clinical Methods: Most of the course was doing roleplays, where one student was a therapist and the other was a patient. Jampel gave advice about how to improve and what things you did well. Almost no reading. MUST participate and critique your classmates during the roleplays. Best prof I've had for psych, but he doesn't have real office hours.

Dr. Jampel is a great professor. He's interesting, entertaining, and extremely helpful for those interested in clinical psychology. There really isn't much work for this class - only one final paper. The rest of your grade comes from class participation and role playing.

Jampel is a wonderful professor for abnormal psych. He is an experienced clinician, so his anecdotes really bring the material to life. I definitely recommend his class to anyone who likes psychology.
Jampel is awesome!  He really knows what he is talking about, encourages other opinions, and is a great clinician!  I have learned a lot from him.

Denby was a real gem who actively tried to get to know us as students and make philosophy interesting for us. Even though I can't tell you anything about philosophy today and definitely faked it until I made it with the papers he assigned, he acknowledged that I was trying and I still received very good grades.

I absolutely loved professor Denby. Intro to Ethics gave me such a break with all my econ/math heavy classes. Professor Denby is really good at explaining difficult concepts with intuitive examples and is hilarious. I wish I had more time at Tufts left to take another class with him.

This is my second semester with Denby and I rave about him to anyone who will listen. I came into Tufts undecided and after two classes with him, I'm seriously considering a philosophy major. His lectures are clear and he makes them interesting with little jokes. The concepts can be a bit hard to grasp but he is super helpful. He's the best.

Denby is one of those professors who can make listening to a lecture every class actually interesting and engaging. He delivers complex philosophical theories in coherent and meaningful ways to students and cares immensely about his class. Take a class with him and you will not regret it.
Denby makes a ton of dad jokes during lecture, but overall he's a really great professor. Really accessible outside of class and generous with extensions.

Denby is a brilliant, witty and fun professor. He really knows the content and actively tries to get students to participate. Asks interesting questions. Papers are graded for phil concepts, not 5 paragraph essay form. Metaphysics is tedious, but it was a great class and I wish I could take more with him. Go to lecture. Easy grader.
teacherRatingTags: ['So many papers', 'Amazing lectures', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: Incredibly clear and straightforward lectures and essay topics. The four essays are graded very fairly, and he is more than willing to help you with concepts or to improve your writing. His British wit helps make dry topics more interesting. If Denby's available as a professor for intro to philosophy, take it with him.
Very straightforward, clear about what he wants. He makes the homework challenging but also a lenient grader. Great sense of humor as well.
The class was at a good pace. He was very good at answering questions and clearing up misunderstandings.

Very clear and interesting. Does his best to deliver content beyond the syllabus, and does a great job of being accessible and helpful. Took logic with him; highly recommend it. And some pretty classic British humor to keep things light
My favorite professor at Tufts. Easily approachable, humorous and crystal clear in his expectations. You learn a lot from his classes and papers, but the work is more than manageable.

Denby is an incredibly engaging professor with total mastery of the subject. If you are interested in philosophy (especially on an introductory level), the topics will keep you engaged. Make sure to stop by his office hours, it is absolutely worth your time.

I took the course PassFail.  The TAs are mainly the people who decide your grade because they are the ones grading your paper.  Grades consisted of only papers - no tests, no participation, no attendance.

Overall a good professor and very clear in lectures. He takes a while to explain each topic, but he stays on point so you really get it. He's sort of a funny guy and tries hard to make lecture interesting by encouraging participation. The grade is completely based on a few essays. Take it if you want to learn some ethics but be graded on writing.

If you're not really interested in the course material, his lectures can be boring at times. The papers themselves are straightforward if you follow exactly what the TA describes. Reading is incredibly optional (but do some while you write the paper).

Denby is one of the best professors at Tufts. He is clear, gives great lectures, and knows the material incredibly well. Everyone should take a class with him even if you aren't particularly interested in philosophy.

Prof. Denby is witty (British humor), interested and interesting, and provides very clear explanations of abstract philosophical concepts. I would highly recommend this professor—he is one of the best lecturers I've had at Tufts.

Amazing amazing professor! Denby is witty, funny, and extremely personal. For an intro phil class (took for eng 2) I learned so much about analyzing arguments. Provides you with all info needed to complete papers and allows you to pretty much write on whatever has been discussed in class. Highly recommend, don't miss out taking a class with Denby.

You don't have to like philosophy to take Denby's classes; his enthusiasm lights up the most boring of subjects.  Lots of discussion for a large lecture class, and most of it is interesting.  The papers are easy, and the class is clearly organized.  Watch out for Denby's morbid sense of humor though - it will come up when you least expect it.

Denby is a great lecturer.  Pay extra attention to the outlines he provides on Trunk, as they will help with notes organization.  Take LOTS of notes and you will have all the info for the papers, which are the ONLY grades. (3 or 4).  If you aren't interested in the subject matter, you will get a little bored.

good overall teacher. his classes are usually the whole grade based on 4 papers... this is good in some ways but I had a a hard time with the first one, it would have been better to have some more guidance. but he really covers the material well if you can stay interested in class

Good professor, but it would have helped if he went over with us more what he expected for the papers, which were the whole grade for the class. The lectures can be boring unless you're really interested.You don't really have to do the reading if you pay attention in class.
Great, funny guy.  Boring subject matter, which would be unbearable if he weren't so funny/awesome.  Easy class.  Reading is extremely optional.

This class is rather boring. It focuses completely on moral theories, which is rather dry. Prof Denby, however, is a great teacher! He is funny and covers the material very well. Some of the theories can be complicated, but he was very clear and helpful. I enjoyed him, but not the class.

Very interesting class. Teacher knows the topic well, is hilarious and presents arguments and topics clearly.  While readings are absolutely not necessary, attendance is.  Go to class, it's fun and if you like the topic, you'll find it easy and fun to write the papers.   Overall, great class, great teacher.

Clear and effective lectures and notes. Prof. Denby is a humorous, able teacher who's always around if you need help, either by e-mail or in person. Take a class with him if you want to learn philosophy and if you want to learn how to think critically.

Prof Denby is by far one of the best teachers I have ever encountered in any school.  Once you take his class, you will realize that he is completely and only interested in his students' education. subject is kind of dry, and often hard to keep awake. Readings in too small print, often "winding" and pointless. Helps a lot to highlight in text and write in margins. Professor is jovial. Overall, its boring for me.

Denby has a brilliant grasp of the topics he teaches in this course, which is structured effectively. A lively lecturer.  Witty and willing to engage in discussions and tolerate dissent.  A fine teacher who manages his classes well.
Denby is the shiznit.  Though the material is a tad dry and dense, he makes it interesting through his lively discussions.  He def got me interested in philosophy.  Take his class if you can!
very helpful, class was pretty easy, reading was hard, but it didnt matter too much, only a few papers, he says in class exactly what to write.  more important to go to class than read

A great guy, but sometimes seems as if he's lecturing for his own benefit. This class has definitely gotten better with time though, finally becoming more discussion less lecture. Overall a good professor.

meh

just a great teacher in my experience

Legitimately the most intellectually capable person I have ever learned from or met. His classes aren't easy, but you will find yourself putting in the effort necessary to do well, he just has that effect. Amazing

War and Terrorism was a very engaging and interesting class. Prof McPherson changed the way I think about the use of violence.

rComments: He's a good guy. Not too tough on grading, and goes veryyyy in detail on his explanations. Disorganized and messy handwriting on board, but he's smart and we talk a lot in class. He REALLY knows his stuff.  Very very approachable and willing to help. His class made me want to major in phil! He keeps it very discussion-based which is important for everyone to be engaged. Great class overall and a patient professor who cares!

Unexpectedly, I had a great time in Phil1. I am neither interested in Philosophy, nor a good writer. Still, I enjoyed professor's McConnel's class. He is an easy grader and always willing to help. Dr. McConnell is a hilarious professor. His classes can be a bit boring but he makes you think. His grading does not always make sense, but he definitely helps you become a better writer. One of the most thought provoking classes I have ever taken.  Prof McConnell is not the most interesting teacher but by the time you leave the class, you're sure to be a better writer.

this professor is really interested in the material but pretty monotone; sometimes i wanted to fall asleep in class! his essay topics are pretty broad but i stopped taking notes because they didn't apply to the topics. he loves what he teaches but has a hard time sharing that with the students. this class is NOT discussion based, which was sad.

very knowledgable and well versed on his sujbect matter. His lectures can ramble and sometimes he takes 2 hours to say what could be said in 30 minutes. If you're going to ask us to supply you with stamps and envelopes as a pre-requisite to passing your course then for God sakes man, at least mail us the darn final exams sooner than 4 months after they were initially turned in.  Seriously, get it together dude.
