He's a good lecturer and accessible in office hours. One of his tests was really fair, and the other was very challenging. Overall a good teacher.

Glaser is a great lecturer and clearly cares about students. The lectures are sometimes dry and there is a lot of reading. Readings are very important for the exams and the IDs can be tricky, which makes it harder to do well in the class.

Prof. Glaser is an absolutely great teacher.  His lectures are interesting and enjoyable to attend, and he inserts funny stories here and there to help students better understand his points.  A lot of the reading is important, but if you're behind schedule it's no big deal, just have it done for the final.  Great course, even better professor.

Something about his class is very soothing and enjoyable. He's very clear and approachable, and just a very nice guy.  He's a centrist and even then does not inject own politics into the class.  Organizes powerpoints well & does a killer Reagan.  Not that much reading, and you can skip it occasionally.  But you'll feel bad since he's so darn nice.

He's a great professor. He lectures in a very easy-to-understand way, and he's quite knowledgeable in his field. The lectures are enjoyable to go to, and the class is easy enough to do well in if you go to lecture. He assigns reading, but it's not crucial (although quite helpful).

Very interesting lecturer. His lectures will keep you engaged. Exams are hard, and you have to study all of the material. Paper is difficult but interesting. Good amount of reading, back-loaded towards end of semester.
Excellent lectures. I actually looked forward to going to class.
Fantastic teacher, fantastic guy. I wish he taught more classes. One of my favorites that I've had at Tufts.

He is an excellent professor. His lectures engage you, he's a very good public speaker. On the personal side, he's a very helpful, nice fatherly figure. His class is, however, quite challenging b. Unlike what other people said, the readings are absolutely crucial to getting a good grade in the class. Recitations are pretty useless though.

He is a wonderful, wonderful teacher who knows so much about the inside of politics, congress, and especially the supreme court that every class is bound to be filled with at least two or three anecdotes.  Class is hard even if you know your stuff, due to infrequency of tests (mid+final) and how they concentrate on only a few specific areas.
Great class, Glaser is a good prof and will tell you what you need to know for the class.  Eager to help people, always free to help.

Glaser is meh. He's not fabulous and he's not horrible. I dont understand the people who say he is amazing. He's just a pretty average teacher with a few interesting stories. A lot of reading assigned but basically none of it is really required. Recitation is lame. I wouldn't highly recommend this teacher but i wouldnt diss him either...

Glaser is witty and interesting, I really enjoyed going to class. There are way too many readings and most of them are pretty boring, but you can get away with only doing a few of them. Going to lectures was helpful, but I have mixed feelings about the recitations and TAs. Fortunately, almost all of the classes are lectures.

Very good, clear lecturer.  Makes it very clear what he wants out of you and how to get a good grade.  Go to class or get notes from someone else, tests based MOSTLY on lecture.  I got away without doing much reading, even though he assigns a lot.

He is a great lecturer but also the most arrogant man I have ever met. I mean the guy thinks he is God. Also the TA's are horrible and don't know anything. Glaser doesn't know most of his students either.
He is the MAN. He is an engaging lecturer and if you ever go to his office hours, he is very very friendly and helpful. The person below is an idiot.

TERRIBLE class. The lecture was so unstructured, the TA's are the most careless people ever, and the class was just bad. Whatever you do, just hope that you get an easy TA, because some people get lucky and get an easy TA and others get screwed.
interesting class. dynamic/funny speaker.
I dropped his class after 2 weeks.  Very uninteresting, always went over time.
Great class!

Nice guy. Good teacher. Hot butt!

awesome!

Good guy w/ great stories and experiences
very accessible, clear lectures, interesting stories, great organization

Take ANY class available with Glaser. He's fun, interesting and knows his stuff!

Prof. Glaser is incredible. Hands down one of the best professors I have had in 4 years at Tufts. If you do all the homework and study hard from the beginning, it is very possible to get in the A range while learning a ton. MG makes every single lecture interesting and genuinely cares about every single student's success.

MG is a professor that will know your name even if you don't make an effort to connect with her. She can be brisk and will call you out for not paying attention or knowing what's going on, but she truly cares about teaching her students and works hard to make sure everyone knows what's going on. She also is very accessible in and outside of class.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Clear grading criteria', 'Tough grader']

rComments: She is a very tough grader. However, you can learn a lot from her class, and she is an INCREDIBLE person. Highly recommended, but get ready not to get an A.

Professor Glaser is one of the good ones. She seems to be a little over-hyped, but she is definitely a great educator. Spending time in the classroom I really got the sense that she cared about and understood the experience of each one of her students.
Best professor I have ever had. Knew so much about all of her students even if you never talked to her.

Really great teacher with a lot of enthusiasm in class.   She really cares and is very passionate about the class.   Great teacher and is very clear in how to do problems and what you need.  She is big on showing you only what you have to do, which is great!

Prof Glaser is one of my favorite professors on campus. I took calc 2 as a requirement and I could not believe how easy she made it. She explains everything clearly, makes herself available. and gets to know her students. All around amazing teacher. I wish she taught more of my classes. Highly recommend her classes.

Great teacher!! Any class you need that she is teaching, take it. She really wants you to do well and teaches well. It's easy to pay attention to her and she makes difficult material easier. I really wish I had more classes with her. Textbook is used for HW every other day and you should go to every class. Definitely one of the best teachers here.

Mary is awesome. The best math professor I have ever had period. She is extremely clear and moves pretty swiftly in her lectures. However you can ALWAYS ask questions and she is always willing to help in office hours. Her test cover the course material. They don't try to trick you in any way but they can be difficult due to the topic covered.
BEST PROFESSOR EVER. She's amazing, makes all concepts extremely clear, and is always entertaining in class. I would take every class she teaches if I could.
She's a great professor. If you go to her office hours, she helps you with whatever you need. Always provides useful examples during classtime and takes time to go over homework questions.
Mary Glaser is the best math teacher I have ever had. She made what was already fairly simple and easy to understand even simpler and easier.
best teacher i had this semester!  she's down to earth and makes class fly by.  she talks fast but she's explains things clearly.  really really great.

Extra-mile kind of teacher, who follows up on students outside of class and is quick to give extensions or mid-class breaks when needed.  Also very skilled at making concepts intuitive and easy to understand, and fairly high-energy.  Highly recommend.

Professor Glaser is wonderful.  She's funny and is able to explain the material in many ways in order to help her students.  She's also very accessible and willing to give extra help.  Gives extra materials that other professors don't offer and prepares students well for exams.  Difficult material, but it would be with any professor.
Glaser is a great professor. She's funny and her explanations are crystal clear. After taking Hahn, she is a breath of fresh air.
Great presence and fun sense of humor. Really accesible and energetic. Taught material through lots of useful examples.
Excellent teacher, really helps the class grasp material

Very nice teacher who explains things very well and always clarifies if you don't get it. Her office hours aren't helpful, but she's surprisingly quick in responding to e-mails, and she's good at that too; a little too enthusiastic about sports in general, which gets annoying quick; tests are fairly easy if you study enough; overall a great teacher

She is the most helpful teacher I have ever had.  I did poorly on the tests but she helped me tons in office hours and after doing well on the final (thanks to her) I finished with a decent grade.  She really cares about her students and wants to see them succeed.  She does move somewhat fast, but otherwise she is an excellent professor.
SHe is the best math teacher that I have ever had. She prepares you very well for tests...my class always had the higher average than other classes.
she's the best teacher ever! funny as hell, sometimes she gives u the hw solutions, sweet! the review before a test is extremely helpful!!!

very interesting, very cool teacher. moves quickly yet clearly through material, as stated in a different entry. quirky sense of humor makes class much more interesting. glaser is very enthusiastic in teaching or at least calc. very random, really great teacher
The best math teacher I have ever had. She moves fast, but in a very clear way. She is the funniest person, and even has her own band!!
I admit... I didn't frequent this class frequently, but when I did, she was a great teacher.
I would take any class taught by P. Glaser again.

Awesome professor, taught tough material very clearly. Also scores points because she is a sports fan, although she had some sort of internal conflict between the Red Sox and Yankees. Overall a great professor and a decent class.

She is a great teacher...clear, interesting explanations, and she is very excited about the material.  Presents it in novel ways.  I bombed this course because I didn't do the homework, so I forgot everything by the final--I wasted the opportunity of having such a great teacher...doh!
Having her in 1996 made me want to be a math major.  (Now I'm a math teacher myself!)  She is a smart confident woman and one of the best teachers I've ever had.
Great teacher. Clear, concise, and very organized.  Highlights for Children!
Best teacher I've ever had in my life, and best professor in the math department by far. Take any and all classes you can that she teaches! Great advisor too.
Very clear and helpful.
very organized, interesting person in a funny way (sushi earings).
Wonderful teacher.

she is amazing, she provides just the right amount of theory with examples!

even tho im not a math major, she made calc fun, and yes it is possible!
Marty is the best english teacher you will ever have. insightful and open. In my class we watched movies and compared them to books. Everything is always applied, the essay prompts are simple.

Ozzy is incredibly intelligent, engaging, and funny. I consider myself very lucky to have had him as a professor. Although he will no longer be teaching at Tufts after this year, I am sure that he will do great things two stops away at Harvard. Learning from him was a true privilege.

Ozzy is the best! I honestly wish that I could take Arabic with him forever! Arabic is a hard language but he is super funny and nice. He makes the class 1000 times better. He is willing to help if you are confused about anything. Arabic is a commitment but it is a very satisfying, you learn a lot. TAKE ARABIC WITH OZZY!!!

Ozzy is the cutest lil man ever, absolutely love him as a person. His class is definitely no walk in the park, though, and his workload will likely be your most demanding class. It is very conversationally oriented, so you must participate. He's very easy going and willing to give help and extend deadlines. The class is overall enjoyable I think.
Great guy who is happy to help. He makes Arabic learnable.
Very funny.  Makes class fun, tries to get everyone involved.  He will often introduce some concepts a few weeks before you need to know them - I found this helpful.
Take Arabic 1 and 2 with him and it will be a complete blast!

I had Ozzy for Arabic 1 and 2, he's awesome. He's super fun in class and a relatively easy grader. He understands that Arabic is a crazily difficult language and factors that in when looking over homework, presentations, etc. I would recommend Ozzy highly, he's a boss.
Ozzy is the best! He'll make you laugh every class and truly takes an interest in his students. take arabic with him!
Ozzy is the best! I learned so much from him. (He's also easy on the eyes...)

Creeden is really nice and helpful--much better than the other Finance prof. He presents clearly and he brings cookies. Plus: he's actually a Venture Capitalist so he knows the subject more thoroughly than a textbook could teach you.
STOLP is the absolute man! Hands-down the best course I ever took at Tufts.

This was one of the least enjoyable classes I've ever taken, which was disappointing, because materials is a very interesting field. Burke was vague and unclear about everything and seemed unwilling to answer many questions with a fear she might get something wrong. Equations were unexplained and material for tests was somewhat random.
She's a great instructor. Gives very helpful feedback and make sure self available to answer any questions in order to clarify when needed.

Silvia was very engaging. Excellent lectures. Supportive of the students. Very receptive to students' feedback. Useful grading rubrics. She is enthusiastic and energetic, and wants the same from students. If you're hard working, you'll love this class.

Silvia is overly nice about everything. She gives 0% negative feedback even when the grade is not perfect. Is obtuse and not open to any new ideas or interpretations. Prefers the fly on the wall to the involved student.
Is helpful if you go see her but very annoying when grading essays. If writing isn't your thing I suggest another professor.

I took intro psych with Thomas in Fall 2015, and she's a very cool professor.  It was admittedly a challenging class, but not as unreasonable as others made it out to be.  I enjoyed the class and learned a lot.  If you actually read the textbook and pay attention in class, you'll have a good time.
Stay away! I'm sure Professor Thomas is a nice person, but she is really not a good teacher.

Worst professor I have had at Tufts so far. Her tests are very difficult, almost as if she was deliberately trying to trip you up. Had to take the class twice because I failed her tests. Interestingly enough, I did much better on the exams written by other lecturers. Do not take this class with Professor Thomas, it's just not worth it.

The tests do not test your knowledge of the material and are designed to trick you because the course is a weed out course. No matter how much you studied, there would be information that you wouldn't know.
Her tests are awful. They truly do not test your knowledge, even if you studied everything you could find. Half of the fall 2015 semester pass/failed it because it is a gpa killer. DO NOT TAKE.

Not many positive things to say. She sometimes tries to be funny and mostly seems to enjoy teaching. However, she is pompous and overbearing. She clearly does not always know her topic. I did not enjoy when she taught the class. Tests were too hard and there were many drops. Absolutely loved the material, but would not take again because of her.

Took Applying Cognition to Education with her (awesome class!). It was a 6 person discussion based course. She was responsive to students and listened to their opinions and concerns, the material was fascinating, she seemed genuinely interested in it, and was creative and fun in lesson design and discussion. Super smart and kind!

Class has an average of C-. No curves, which I don't really understand since the whole class isn't doing too hot. Throws weird questions on the exam that focus on very specific details in the READING, not even from her own lecture. Talks about herself and her own lecture a lot. Would not recommend taking a class with her.

rComments: Her lectures are incredibly disorganized. Often times she seems more concerned with plugging her own research than presenting anything of value. I had a hard time with how she paced the lectures - she pauses a lot when she talks, which can make it difficult to stay focused.

I really liked the topics discussed, but her powerpoints were confusing and she sometimes rushed through important material that then appeared on quizzes. She sometimes couldn't answer questions on the spot. Other than that, she is nice.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: Professor Thomas is awesome!  Her research on memory, cognition, and aging is SUPER interesting and she always incorporates interesting and relevant examples from her research into the class!  Tests were challenging but if you put in a little extra study time they were manageable and fair.  I'm totally declaring a psych major!

She's a really nice woman and not boring to listen to during lectures, but her lecture power points are very disorganized. Tests were awful as there were questions on material never mentioned, and it was apparent that half of the questions were written by her TA who barely spoke english.

Terrible professor, terrible lecturer. Uses the class to promote her research and makes herself sound a lot smarter than she really is. Rushes through the slides, which are already incomprehensible. Take this class with another professor.

The worse professor I have had at Tufts. She has absolutely no clue what she's doing, but she thinks she does. She is unable to answer questions on the spot and her multiple choice exams make absolutely no sense. Avoid this professor at all costs.

The worst professor I've had at Tufts.  When asked to clarify, she usually says "well, i don't really know. I could look it up, but I probably won't."  She never came to proctor any of her own exams, which may have been helpful, seeing as her multiple choice questions were completely incomprehensible. Listen to the other rating. Avoid at all costs.

Thomas is a terrible psych professor. Her lectures are unclear, filled with typos, and she'll waste class time talking about herself. The exam she gave was poorly written, and she was of no help when it came to asking questions about what material to study. Avoid her at all costs.
Very caring

Good guy, rambles often but at least it's interesting usually. you dont have to read anything he assigns but class is awkward if no one else does either. i wouldn't recommend his class if you have zero interest in the environment/nature. his essay feedback is helpful but you'll have to do more than what he put in order to get that A normally

I took his Nature in Writing class. The class does get boring sometimes, but the books he chooses are generally good and he is clear about what he wants. The final grade is composed of 4 essays basically but he gives good feedback on the drafts. Generally a pretty good class.

Has a tendency to ramble but very well intentioned. I thought he was mostly interesting but not everybody did. The final grade is entirely based on four six-page essays but you have to write six two-page papers as well. He gives a lot of feedback so I thought the class was pretty easy if not the most riveting.

I took his nature and writing class. I'm interested in that topic, which is why i chose to take this class over all the other English 2 courses offered. I enjoyed his assignments very much, even though i had to put a lot of time and thought into it--isn't that the nature of writing? Prof. Gardner is a very understanding, kind, and open teacher.

I took Nature and Writing. In class, he just rambles about random things. Although you have to go, you really don't need to be paying attention. You have to write about five 2 page essays about strange topics and then four 6 pagers about the environment. You don't get your grade until the end of the semester though.

His feedback is extensive and very helpful.  You will always be able to find a topic that interests you.  There is alot of writing, about 40 pages over the semester, but you will come out a much better writer.  Be warned, he does not give out many grades but he is a very fair grader and is very flexible with final draft deadlines.
We spend most of class discussing his random thoughts.  Also Geoff is very vague about the essays and what he actually wants.  If you want to be able to track your grade, avoid him.
His questions are thought-provoking and he is a great guy, however you'd better adapt to his ideas of what 'correct' english is. Also, be pepared fr a surprise when you get your grade.
So random... interesting, but if you care about your GPA avoid this guy.
Good class, and he was always clear about what he expected. doesnt give letter grades until the last day, somewhat annoying, but if you want a good laid back, thought provoking class, take his.
No Comments
He does a great job looking over your work and improving it.

He is an interesting teacher.  He looks at your work carefully and provides you with feedback, but you won't master the principles of english.  His topics and course outline is intriguing but it's a little difficult to improve your writing.

Gardner is a very unbiased english teacher, hard to find these days.  Take anything and everything he teaches.  He doesnt help you write any better, but who needs to that goes to Tufts.  Fortunately his topics are well thought out and interesting.
good teacher, recommend taking anything he teaches

Doris is so so great; I can't say enough great things about her. My German improved more in one year of classes with her than it did while taking German for 8 years during middle and high school. If you are taking German at Tufts, be sure to take a class with her.
Just a really awesome nice professor.

I love Doris! You will learn SO much German. Tells lots of funny stories from Bavaria. Relatively easy grader on tests. She's big on punctuality- don't be late. Lots of homework but it's easy stuff. The online textbook is incredibly annoying but I think the whole German department uses it anyway.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Gives good feedback', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: She is very nice and has helped me as someone who has never taken German before to be very interested in the language. She is helpful especially if you see her for office hours. Lots of homework, but its not challenging, it helps you learn.

Doris is a strong teacher and definitely meets students where they're at. I struggle with German and she has been an inspiration and a half. I love everyone in the German department but have a particular fondness for Doris. Definitely take her classes.
She grades much harder than the other German professors. Be warned! She will teach you more German, but you'll have to work harder for it.

Doris is literally the coolest. She is very clear and teaches you a TON of German. You do fun skits and a movie project which can be really awesome if you want it to be. She's also so understanding. I had a family emergency the night before one of our exams and she let me make it up, no questions asked. Do your homework and you'll get a good grade.
Doris is awesome. She has a little bit of hardass in her, but she's a great teacher and her classes are great if you put in the effort.
Doris is a great professor. She can be a bit particular sometimes, but she's from Bavaria and knows and loves the German language, and class is definitely varied.

I took American Youth Revolt and Revolution with Prof. Abowd, learned a ton, really enjoyed the class. so far capricious and weird political agenda - seems anti US. i don't feel comfortable

*thumbs up*
Intense lecturer and excellent scholar/activist!
superb teacher --hard but great with students

Abowd deeply cares about his students and subject matter. He will far out of his way (despite how busy he is) to assist his students. If you put in the effort you will absolutely be rewarded.
Great teacher--always helpful--charasmatic.

Abowd is really, really tough grader but his human rights course was amazing. I learned so much but had to work so hard just to get a B. Take the course but only if you have the time to devote to it.
A professor who actually cares about students. The class was sometimes too demanding but you will learn so much if you work. Nice guy, too.

The material for this class is really interesting, and some of the ethnographies are great. However, Abowd's lectures are inconsistent and can be scattered. Good teacher but hard to follow sometimes, classes often disorganized. Really listens to students and office hours were helpful.
pop culture class was very interesting. This professor was strong.
This course on human rights rights was spectacular. Abowd is really good lecturer and nice guy. The course was difficult though and it was a lot of work just to get a B. Recommended.
Superb teacher. He involves students in class discussion and encourages open debate (even if you disagree with his mostly radical views on politics). Very tough but usually fair.
Amazing professor who showed respect for all. The readings were challenging but they were also great.

I don't know what this other reviewer is thinking. Abowd is my favorite professor. He is so dedicated to getting to know his students and always willing to clarify anything in office hours. He genuinely respects what his students have to say and the class is very discussion based. He uses a variety of media and the readings are long but great.

He is at Harvard now so a TA does all his grading.  His TA Mark is VERY hard, but if you can grow a tough skin you'll learn a lot from Mark.  Wynne is much kinder.  Prof. Robichaud is dynamic, engaging, and eager to help, if you ask for it.  There is a lot to read and you may have to reread assignments to really understand the material.  Worth it!

Knowledgeable, interesting lecture - summarizes the hefty reading - but you still have two or more hours of reading. The TA's - excellent! The Prof - disorganized. Syllabus changes, date changes  stress. If you like philosophy, this is a great prof. If you like poli-sci - skip it.

Now that he's at Harvard, his retinue of graduate assistance seem to have taken away one of his weakness mentioned above. not cool.

Disorganized and full of excuses. He waited until after we could no longer drop the class before giving us any clue how we were doing in the class. I think he is lazy. In retrospect, this class was disappointing. Although Chris can be funny and engaging at times, his egotism is a turn off. Now having taken upper level philosophy courses that were more interesting and far easier, I'd recommend Intro with another lecturer.

Always kept class interesting and would relate things like The Matrix, Star Wars, Batman, etc. to what we were learning. Some of the readings were a bit dense or dry, but he was good at explaining things to an intro to phil class. Slow at grading papers, but good professor.
Very good. Gives candy in class. Take him for es5
Very good teacher but he tends to move very quickly
Great teacher, really covers all material well.  Moves a bit fast but by far the best of the teachers for ES5.  Really good slides and very honest about what will be on tests.

One of the best teachers I had at Tufts. He pushes you and makes sure you are engaged in class. He will call on you at random to go over the readings so it definitely keeps you on your toes. If you do the readings (15min) and take some notes, you will do great.
He makes it seem like he's gonna give the whole class As and then you'll get a B- and be like what just happened?

Lectures get kind of boring and he isn't very clear on what he teaches. His grading is also very arbitrary, especially on the research paper. Tests themselves aren't too challenging. His lectures were so irrelevant that you could sleep through them daily and still pass the class- provided that you knew how to complete ridiculously long and detail oriented midterms and finals on your own. teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Tough grader', 'So many papers']

Tv is literally awful. You have the option to take a different EN-1 class so DO IT. His lectures are disorganized, contribute nothing to the class, and use high level math for an intro level course. I wrote over 20 pages for the midterm paper and got an 85. All my friends got A+'s in their EN1 classes while i barely got a B
He's helpful outside of class and really nice, but isn't that good of a lecturer in class.

Hardest class you'll take as an EE or CPE. He's a genius, but beware that as a non-physicist you may have trouble following his ridiculous math capability. Fairest grader on campus. Do the readings before class. And pray.

Great professor for E&M!  He is funny in lecture, which is hard to do for a tough subject like this.  He is easy to talk to outside of class and it is obvious that he really cares that we not only learn the material, but learn how to learn.   His tangential stories are the best too!

Remco did a fantastic job teaching Comp11. Class is easy to learn from because he prepares example programs before each class. He is the professor that will definitely give you great help, if you often go to talk with him.  It feels much more comfortable to take his higher level courses :)
He's no Hescott, but he's a great professor nonetheless. :]
Great!

Awful. We had John Hodgman come in and he seemed pretty cool so take this class with him. She's a good professor and has great speakers come in all the time.  The class is very group based and requires a lot of time outside the classroom.  It's a requirement and not too painful to get through.

She is great for English. Chooses interesting reading, that are not overwhelming. The essays are also not hard and you have plenty of time to do them. She meets with each student individually and really cares about your progress.
Love the class!
great
Very mellow, but extremely funny and charismatic. Fun :). Knows her stuff and teaches it well. Really good step by step instruction. Made me a better writer :)

best, hardest &most rewarding class I have ever taken. Prof Hammer really wants his students to succeed, very accessible, explains it to you in crazy ways to help you understand, easy to talk to about physics or life. unconventional class but you ACTUALLY learn, disliked by ppl who just want to use equations & not understand.  tough but worth it 3

He does an awful job of explaining and he's very condescending. Avoid if you can!

He's from the Education Department, but he knows his stuff. His lecture style is hard to get use to, but I feel like I learned physics and why things work the way they do. He is SO extremely helpful outside of class as well. Take Physics 11 with him!

Seems to want students to succeed, but grading system seems set up almost to set up students to do poorly. Lectures could be more clear, and recitations leave more questions asked than answers explained

He's one of the nicest professors I've met here at Tufts. Extremely accessible and stresses understanding the concepts above just memorizing formulas. Hammer makes himself very available to help and is genuinely concerned with students' progress. Overall a very good teacher with a difficult but rewarding class.

Prof. Spielberg was the best teacher I had at Tufts. Alissa is an intelligent, nice person. She clearly cares a lot about CH, but as a professor, she has some flaws. Your grade is mostly based on whether you get a hard or easy TA.  The grading criteria is vague and you're never given a clear description of what is expected so it is extremely difficult to succeed unless you already know a great deal of Mythology and are knowledgable in classics.

Professor Beaulieu is amazing! In my class there a lot of vocab memorization (which ended up being super helpful), but she is always willing to help through email or office hours. Her lectures are clear and fun. She's spunky and just overall a great prof.

teacherRatingTags: ['Clear grading criteria', 'Beware of pop quizzes', 'So many papers']

rComments: LOVE her. She's my advisor, which is why I took the class in the first place, and it was amazing. The cool thing about this class is that Beaulieu shows you how to do good research without making it seem daunting. Really interesting, and can honestly say I learned so much.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Beware of pop quizzes', 'Amazing lectures']

rComments: Prof Beaulieu is the sweetest professor ever. She's such a nerd for Classics and loves what she teaches. I had her two semesters in a row and I don't regret it.

Professor Beaulieu was incredible. Her lectures are interesting and engaging, even if she goes off on a brief tangent, it's relevant and she knows exactly what she's talking about. She's really nice, but her lectures are quite unorganized. I would highly recommend recording / making HIGHLY detailed notes on the lectures. Talk to the TAs and her if you have help, she's always ready to help you if you're stuck on something.

I loved this class, Professor Beaulieu is very enthusiastic and interesting.  The class requires a lot of participation which motivated me to try hard and helped me grasp the material.  I hope to take another class with her in the future!!
Very fun professor with a cute accent and appearance. Very straight forward teaching and testing. If she talks about it, it will probably be on the exam.

Professor Beaulieu is one of my favorite professors at Tufts. She is extremely encouraging and enthusiastic about the material. He is very clear, very helpful, Diff EQ is the hardest class at Tufts. Take it with a friend (more than one in case they drop) and do every homework.

hes great.

She is an ok professor. She clearly knows a lot about her subject and will make a point of finding the answers to any questions she doesn't know. She is a tough grader for papers though, and is a real stickler for grammar. And sometimes her lectures are a bit boring.

Professor Ford usually ask students a lot of questions during his lectures encouraging participation and deep thinking.

A great teacher that really cares about her students. She makes German fun and keeps it interesting. Probably my favorite teacher I've encountered so far. If you take a German class which she teaches, take her section!

Petrov's a pretty good Russian teacher. She uses the textbook a lot in class and the workbook for homeworks. The homework takes up a decent amount of time. The tests aren't too hard if you study and she grades nice enough. One MAJOR problem is that she holds us as much as seven minutes after class so I would always be late for my next class

Otlychno! (Excellent!) Very kind, always helpful, and really concerned with her students' progress. Very helpful in learning Russian (not that hard a language, actually) and really interested in her subject. Couldn't ask for more!

Thoroughly mediocre language professor. She's helpful and sweet, but the class is not particularly well-organized or challenging. Russian language, on the other hand, is VERY difficult, and this class (and her others) are not rigorous enough.

Honestly, Ming has been the best lecturer I've had since coming to Tufts. I've never seen anyone as invested as him in his students' not only success, but best performance. Would take any class with him, any day.
take the class. ming is great.

Knowledgeable and points you to many different online resources to augment your learning. Class lectures are fun only because of Ming's quirky (sometimes shouty) lecture style. Can be jarring if you're used to CS classes where professors spoon feed you the information. TL;DR: take Security because it's essential!

Ming is an amazing professor, he is really grounded in reality. He knows how to prepare you for the real world. He cares about his students and is passionate about the topic he teaches. His lectures are not always helpful and you must do your own research and look up examples to do homework. Great individual and professor.

Honestly probably the worst professor I've had at Tufts. He doesn't teach class - just gives assignments and expects you to do the research so that you can learn everything on your own. Lectures are a waste of time - he usually brings in guest lecturers that don't really have anything to do with the class, or just goes on ridiculous tangents.

Honestly the best professor I've had so far at Tufts. He teaches you important things outside of the curriculum and is overall a great guy. People say "he doesn't teach" but he does cover the important topics. The rest can be learned through the notes and codes he posts online.

Ming is great. He is hilarious and engaging, but if you  don't pay attention in class details are going to slip past you. He will expose you to all kinds of new ideas and resources, but will not hold your hand through every little nook and cranny of material. You will get out of the class what you put into it.

Ming's awesome. That's all there is to it. He makes you feel like a peer seeking knowledge instead of some kid who knows nothing. Honestly, I loved taking a course from him and intend to take many more.

Ming's a fine guy, but he was an awful teacher. I know some people love him, but this class was a waste of time. I've heard he was pretty helpful when people went to his office, but that wasn't the problem. It was that I had to learn everything on my own. Might as well have taken an online tutorial over the summer in my spare time.
Ming is the best. He teaches the material well and assigns cool projects. Any class with him will very much be a learn by doing experience.

Responsive via email and gives clear assignments. He structures the course so most learning happens through projects. Lectures are for picking up foundations. I agree with this method and believe that CS is learned best as you build stuff. Would love to see him be more RESPECTFUL and SENSITIVE to students. This will NOT make them worse developers.

Ming is an above average (for Tufts) lecturer, but by far the best professor I've ever had at Tufts.  If you are looking at a teacher that will help and celebrate your successes, give you great life advice, and just all around be an awesome person, that's him. He is what every teacher should aspire to be.   Take a class with him. Get to know him.

Ming does what no other teacher does properly: he teaches you how to teach yourself. Some people complain that they don't learn anything in lecture, but it's because they've missed the point. You take a class with Ming to gain confidence in your ability and be a self-starter, and he is an amazing resource there to help you every step of the way.
Ming is a must-have in the Tufts computer science department. He's ridiculously passionate about everything he teaches and teaches you the things you need to know to be able to learn on your own.

This was a good class and I learned a lot, that being said 90% of the learning was done outside of class. To be fair, Ming makes this very clear from day 1 so there's no trickery going on. Classes are very entertaining, but not very relevant. Ming is very intelligent and truly cares about his students well being, always ready to provide help.

You're probably better off buying a book and teaching yourself. Besides, Ming refers you to google every time you have to learn a new concept or technique. He's a very nice guy, but his lectures are off topic and unhelpful. There are appropriate times to say "RTFM", but it seems like everything I learned in this class I got from google.
I think I'm the only person in Tufts CS who doesn't like Ming, but I hated his class, thought he was obnoxious, and would not recommend taking a class with him to anyone.

Phenomenal professor. He's very understanding about workload and cares about the students. Ming is excited about everything he's doing and it draws you into his teachings. A don't miss in the Tufts CS department.
Great professor. Reason I finally decided to major in CS. Very helpful and cares about the students. Definitely very passionate about subject. Makes class very engaging.

Ming is a very entertaining, exuberant lecturer.  However, his lectures are never on point, and he's all over the place with his explanations.  I feel like he does a very poor job of explaining new concepts as coherent ideas; he tends to instead throw out different points, but never connect them into a single idea.
Take a class with this guy at some point.
It was a good class. He teaches you enough so that you know what questions to ask/Google, but he allows you to do most of the learning. The man is also batsh*t crazy... but we all love him for it.

Great Prof. Knows his stuff. Gives challenging but worthwhile and practical assignments. You have to put in a lot of work on your own, but he'll never run out of things to teach you. Lectures can be hard to follow if you're not at all familiar with the topic of the day.
The best professor ever! He knows the materials so well and manages to explain them clearly and easy to understand.
Favorite professor/class so far at Tufts. Has a sense of humor, but is very focused and clear in his teachings. Writes down great notes!

Professor Panzer is the best professor I have had at Tufts. I consistently show up to lecture having no idea what we are learning today and leave with a fundamental understanding of the concepts. He is exceptionally clear, organized, well-spoken, intelligent, and always willing to help. Take advantage of his excellency while you have it.
teacherRatingTags: ['Respected', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Lots of homework']

rComments: He understands materials very well and is extremely good at public speaking. He can convey complicated ideas very clearly. Could not have asked a better professor like him.
He's SUCH A GOOD teacher he makes everything make sense and he's super nice
He's a truly excellent professor. Very helpful during office hours. His course notes are very organized and he is great at explaining. Very nice outside of class as well.
teacherRatingTags: ['Gives good feedback', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Respected']

rComments: He is really helpful. Some of the topics covered in the class can be difficult but he is really good at simplifying them.

ChBE 175 Is the single best class I've taken at Tufts. Panzer is a god among lecturers, and his feedback is valuable on anything you do. While he's very difficult in other classes, 175 is easier and more relaxed than his other classes. Even the hardest classes are worth taking with Panzer at the helm.

Interesting class that is research-focused instead of textbook-focused. This is by no means a bad thing and, in fact, taught me valuable assets to have a successful research career. As a professor, he is wonderful (as the other comments attest to). Crystal clear, always friendly, and helpful as he can be. Class was relatively easy. Nothing negative

Honestly, a great professor. He's extremely helpful outside of class and crystal clear in class. He posts lectures online, which helps a ton, and he also provides a practice exam. Grading was fair, tests were relevant, and homework was reasonable. Only downside is that more than half of the course is the same as PChem I, but that's not his fault.
AWESOME
The best teacher I have ever had. He taught a very difficult subject, and made it easy to understand.  Great teacher who engages the students well and really wants everyone to succeed. Great!
Panzer is good! He's tough- but he goes through all the material very clearly. Incredibly helpful, engaging, and teaches very well!
He's great, really interested in your learning and goes slow and clearly through the material
Would not recommend.

I did not enjoy this class at all.  Lectures were boring, exercises were pointless (often a mark of an inexperienced teacher).  This is a topic you should learn, but do it with a different professor if you can help it at all.

The way she lectures is extremely boring, and she treated all the students like we were in high school (like forcing every student to submit questions before every class that were almost always useless). With her intolerable personality and random grading, I would recommend taking this class with a different professor.

I don't think that Dr. Chauncey has been rated fairly so far. She's a good lecturer, she's very funny, and she has a good personality. She can scare some students because of her intolerance for cell phones and browsers but if you actually are interested and pay attention, it doesn't matter. Go into her class with an open mind.

By far the worst class I have ever taken. "Dr. C", as she refers to herself, is incapable of delivering a lecture of any interest. She tries to act cool by sitting down for the entire class, when really all this does is make the lecture even less engaging. The grading on tests is incredibly inconsistent and she treats students like they're six.

Terrible lecturer. Openly said that she writes lectures right before giving them.  Not surprising since she often cannot finish the lecture in time or she leaves 10-15 extra minutes at the end. Also includes technical neuroscience terms in lectures without introducing/defining them. VERY UNAPPEALING PERSONALITY. Avoid if you can.

Take a class with her only if you're incapable of any independent thinking and can robotically and compulsively put up with nonsense.  She gives work that should set the standards for purposeless nonsense.  Her interest is students is contingent on them following her instructions verbatim.  Outside thinking and independent ideas are unwelcome.

Great Professor! Really interested in students' understanding and knows how to make this (normally boring) class interesting. Had the whole class over for brunch for presentations on the last day of class. Take a class with her!

Cynthia is extremely understanding. She allows you to ask ANY question during a test. You can ask her what ANY word means, even if it is a word you should definitely know. Sometimes, she allows you to use notes, books, dictionaries on test. She believes that tests are simply chances to "experimentar con la lengua." Her deadlines can be flexible.

She definitely wants all of her students to succeed. Very encouraging of students to come to her office hours, and hosts extra office hours before papers are due. Instead of rejecting a student's answer when it's wrong, she tries to find something interesting about it, which made me feel more comfortable participating. Class wasn't too hard.
Tests were difficult, but she made the classes more fun.  I felt I had a better grasp of Russian with her teaching compared to Nancy.
As russian goes shes a great professor. Can't really make Russian all that easy but she makes the classes bearable and I feel like I learnt a lot more under her then Nancy

Great professor.  Genuinely interested in the language but most importantly, in her students.  Russian is a tough language but she makes it enjoyable.  Knows how to joke around but also how to prepare her students as well.
Great teacher, great classes!

Gavin is a really cool guy who has a lot of great real-world experience. I took his marketing class and loved it! You'll learn a lot, and if you do the work, you will do well. It really depends more on the groups you are put in, but overall would recommend this class and Gavin for sure. Really nice guy too.
Inspiring is the keyword. You not only learn the subject matter, but also valuable life lessons.
Gavin Finn is one of the best teachers at the school. His class is incredibly realistic and he cares for and brings out the best in his students. Highly recommended.
Easily my favorite class at Tufts and the best teacher. He made me think about things in a whole new light and was constantly inspiring and interesting. A must take class for all!

Gavin Finn is a really inspiring man. He has a great back story and knows just about everything there is to know. It's wild. His lectures can be a bit long but he always spends the first hour having group discussion. Ask him anything from branding to finance, he knows it all. Group work was the bulk of the class, working with real companies
Great teacher, but a lot of outside the classroom group work.

I get that the class is supposed to be an easy science A, but he could've at least acted like he cared.  The material was hilariously simplistic and lectures were beyond boring.  Didn't learn a thing, and it was a waste of everyone's time.  Stay away

The class material is very interesting, and as a humanities major I was excited to learn astro. Class was very easy.... but Danilo is an awful teacher! He is no doubt a genius, as he is top of his field, but his class is terrible. Long, dry lectures, repetitive assignments. You don't learn anything, a huge disappointment.

Awful teacher.... absolutely the most boring professor I have ever had. Complete hardo and only cares about his "teaching method." And not an easy A by any means. Do not take this class if you like astronomy, take Wanderers a different semester.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Tough grader', 'Lecture heavy']

rComments: God, it is like watching paint dry listening to him. If you really love anything about science, stay as far away from this class as possible.

No, this class is not an easy A, but if you try at least a little, you can easily do well. Marchesini is really nice, and he loves when students show interest. He offers a ton of extra credit for going to every class, which makes it easier to do well.

I took this class after "Wanderers in Space" to satisfy my Science requirement because I heard it was an easy one. THIS WAS NOT THE CASE. Marchesini is very hard on the matter cuz he's a hardo about astronomy. A lot of tedious work and need to go to class to do well. Not an easy A at all but rather a very hard A. Language barrier & difficult exams

The class wasn't a complete joke, but it was still pretty easy.  I stopped going to class consistently, and then stopped going altogether and still got an A.  If you're genuinely horrific at science then maybe it won't be as easy as I say it was, but if you're looking for a science credit take this class. The other professor was much worse.

Awful. He and the other professor were not clear and often couldn't be understood. They tried to hard to make it a harder class to a point where it wasn't so much harder as it was unorganized. They messed up and had to correct grades a lot, and didn't seem to care about the students. The observation project was not engaging. Don't take this class.

They made the course harder this year. Far less bonus points, and to do well on the exam you actually need to carefully go through the readings. Be careful, it's still one of the easier science classes, but no longer the east A!

Take this class if you are looking to fill a science credit! May seem like a lot of info during lecture, but once you take the first exam you see that you don't really need to pay attention. Tests are VERY easy. Multiple choice, usually with 3 options. Study the powerpoints for the tests and you'll be fine! And funny Italian accent haha

He has a cool Italian accent which makes the lectures more entertaining. Good sense of humor. 3 midterms and a final. He gives you 35 free bonus points on tests so you can get 7 questions wrong and still get a 100. Reading is assigned but lecture slides are all online so you can do well with no reading. Highly recommend for non-science majors.

Pretty funny guy, but lectures are pretty pointless, as most of the time is spent deriving equations and he does not do practice problems.Tests wouldn't have been as hard if we were better prepared from lecture. I worked very hard for this class and didn't feel like it paid off. From what I could tell, Jose didn't care much about the course.

Only Pennington could take a class on the history of Rock n Roll and make me wish I didn't take it. Goes over the time limit of the class and then takes even more time returning the random and grade-wise irrelevant writing prompts, seems not to understand the basics of academic writing or that subject matter is far too easy for the  work assigned.

Prof Pennington cares loads about his students. He's an amazing person most importantly and also an incredible professor. He's passionate about the subjects he teaches and will challenge you to think differently about any topic. He's very knowledgeable. He recognizes hard work so it's up to you to show your interest and if you do, you'll do well.

Pennington is an absolutely wonderful professor. He's a great lecturer and very personable. The kind of guy with whom you could have a 45 minute conversation about ANY kind of music (I've talked to him extensively about Riff Raff and 2 Chainz before). Take any of his classes, but be warned, it is not easy. Papers are tough, but ultimately worth it.

Pennington is the type of professor that can catch your interest with one sentence. He's an amazing lecturer and really wants his students to understand the material and succeed. He makes you work for your grade but in the end its worth it. Great when it comes to help!

Great professor but don't think queer pop is going to be a class that you won't have work for. Lots of papers and reading. Definitely worth it and he's a great professor. I learned a lot and he is super cool and funny. He pushes you to become a better writer and thinker.

Pennington is one of the best professors I've ever had. He's very knowledgeable, highly entertaining, and extremely helpful. He's the kind of professor that you just want to be best friends with. However, don't let that fool you - he's not exactly an easy grader. He wants to be friendly and engaging, but he will also push you to challenge yourself.

Best professor/teacher I've ever had in my academic career. I wish he taught all of my classes. The most intelligent, wonderful, caring, charismatic human. Professor Pennington and his courses (I've taken Queer Pop as well) changed my life.
simply put, just terrible...

History of African-American Music with Pennington was fantastic.  He's a wonderful lecturer and engages the class in some enlightening discussions (even when talking about 2 Live Crew). Exams and papers are not too difficult.  Even casual music fans will love his enthusiasm, charisma, and watching the "Billie Jean" video as part of lecture.

Very enthusiastic about his subject and good at explaining musical concepts for non-music majors. The mid-term and final were straight forward, although he can be a bit vague when grading papers. Overall, a top professor at Tufts, and someone that I would highly recommend.
Extremely passionate professor for History of African-American Music.  Funny, smart, knows his stuff.  Take his class (and talk to him about music and life during office hours.)

TAKE THIS CLASS!! basically, take anything taught by Professor Pennington. He is the most supportive, enthusiastic, and compelling teacher I've had thus far. African American Music was an extremely interesting class, best I had this semester, definitely returning next year for his Black Divas class. He always amazes me with how much he knows.
The best professor I've ever had.
The best teacher I've had at Tufts hands down.  Class material is interesting and lectures are a blast.  Looking forward to taking his classes in the future.  Awesome.

All that is good in the world personified.  He reminds me a little of Carlton from Fresh Prince with his height and bowtie, but his personality couldn't be farther.  The most caring, enthusiastic, purely good professor at Tufts. Trust me, take his class.  I SAID TAKE IT, FOO'!

Three words: Take. This. Course.  History of Rock 'n' Roll is a really fun course, and you will never look at music the same way again!  To top it off, Professor Pennington is awesome at helping his students understand the material.  Also, he claims the textbook is on the exams, but really, the course was easy to understand without it.
History of rock 'n' roll was awesome.  You'll learn so much more than just about the music.  And Pennington is straight up the best professor at Tufts.

She is not an organized professor and her lecture slides aren't useful at all. Her lectures are boring and what she talks about in class is not on the test. The tests are very problem based. She is always available for office hours and will give you ways of increasing your grade. She curves the grades so it's fairly easy to get a good grade.
perhaps one of the easiest econ courses ive taken while at tufts. Gnedenko is also a great professor and very clear in her teaching. Overall 10/10 -- easy, comprehensive, and engaging.

Where to start.  Ekaterina is one of the most frustratingly horrible professors I have ever had.  She makes mistakes on everything, from the solutions of problems to wording questions incorrectly on tests, to concocting quizzes that can't possibly be finished in the allotted time. Bc of all this, u can work hard and have nothing to show for it.

The lectures can be incredibly confusing and frustrating, but reviewing the slides outside of class is actually helpful. A lot of her examples are taken straight from the textbook, so using the 'book is really helpful. She's a lenient grader, however, and very willing to help (although, not she's always as helpful as she thinks she is).

Not the best lecturer. She can be really confusing about the material and does not always explain things clearly. Form study groups to help each other out. If you're a quant econ major you just have to push through. She is a caring professor and is accessible in office hours.

Ec 16 is somewhat challenging and one would benefit from taking linear algebra beforehand or at the same time. Katya is very sweet and helpful in office hours, though she can get derailed in class because the content gets complicated fast. She has all materials well-organized online so what you don't understand in class can be fixed via self-study.

Pretty difficult concepts in general. Lectures are very complicated, but if you ask for help and go to office hours she's very receptive. Tests are way less daunting than the lectures make them seem. I found her a better professor than others seem to on here...

Shes terrible. Tough to understand partially because of her accent and partially because she's just the worst. With that said, it's not too difficult. Read the book and memorize the examples in it, because she pulls a lot of her tests psets from it

Why. WHY did she have to be the only teacher teaching EC16. Terrible...terrible teacher. Lectures have no structure. Her writings on the board make no sense because they are all over the place. Be sure to make plenty of friends in the class, you'll have fun discussions ripping on her.
Unbelievably bad professor.  Never understands the questions, so never successfully answers a questions.  This is NOT the level of education we should be receiving at Tufts.

Professor can't seem to organize her own thoughts and material during lecture and often makes mistakes to her own examples (some of which she can't solve!). Exams are haphazardly planned and usually include questions that are not covered in class, so a lot of self reading is required.

ok, first of all I'm really interested in this subject because I'd like to become a environmental scientist, that aside this is a really interesting class, the prof really knows her stuff, class is not too hard, some exam questions were tough -  you can learn a lot if you participate in the class, do hw, study course material
She's super nice, but not the best lecturer. Easy class though

Not a very good teacher. Going to class is only useful to get her lecture notes but she posts those online later anyways. Study from the problem sets. Her tests are pretty straight-forward. You won't learn very much in her class but its easy to get a pretty good grade.

She has a strong russian accent. However, this class is easy. 3 quizzes: To do well, memorize the powerpoints. 2 midterms (no final): multiple choice, free response and problems. The problems are the EXACT problems from the book with different numbers. The rest, memorize the notes. Easy! And I don't even understand Econ generally
Tests were way too difficult and made the material harder than it should have been. Many students ended up withdrawing after the second midterm. I highly recommend not taking him.
Very condescending and does not explain material well at all. He made Calculus miserable and all of the exams were impossible. Do not recommend taking if you are not a math major!
Horrible Professor and acts like he knows everything about anything. Do not take him if you don't have to. Exams are extremely difficult and looks to take off points for anything.
He's absolutely great. I hated calculus and was able to really understand it and get a great grade from Jamie.
Lectures were organized and clear, which is exactly what you need with these kind of math classes with a ton of sections. He was very helpful outside of class and prepared us well for the exams.

Great professor. Usually great math professors have great handwriting in south korea but his handwriting wasn't the neatest so I thought he was just whatever. But he is actually amazing. Listen to him and he teaches and stresses important stuff so students solve problems in such way that they dont make mistakes in exams.

Great professor. Usually great math professors have great handwriting in south korea but his handwriting wasn't the neatest so I thought he was just whatever. But he is actually amazing. Listen to him and he teaches and stresses important stuff so students solve problems in such way that they dont make mistakes in exams. Personally Math 11 was easy

Wolf has a tough class to teach- hard to make Calc11 interesting, but he tries to be as clear as possible. Best part about him is his availability to students. Always takes the time to go over hw problems and waits after class to answer questions. Don't be afraid of his office hours, but go with specific questions from the hw

Wolf is extremely helpful. His lectures are crystal clear and he explains them in a way that is helpful and comprehensive. If you go for extra help, he is extremely helpful an will stay as long as it takes. He really doesn't like when people talk in his class or when cells go off.

If you went to class (or even just read the powerpoints), it was very easy to do well. Kimball's organization of the course was very clear, and material was presented so that even mathematically challenged people can do fine.

He is unclear in instructions and wording on tests and homework, unhelpful when approached, and unrepentant and unforgiving even when he does admit that you were punished for his lack of clarity in wording.  He is the worst at answering questions of any sort that I have come across.
Just ok teacher in class, but very kind and willing to spend lots of time in office hours.

Did a great job teaching this course and one of the nicest most helpful teachers around.  Definitely sounds like major improvement over past courses - controls is his thing. Added plus was incorporating/reading/acting out the page from the children's book mid-lecture.

Second class I've had with Rife. Lectures are absolutely impossible to understand, unclear notes and many mistakes that make understanding the material difficult. Didn't follow the notation/methods of the textbook, making effective studying nearly impossible. Nice professor, but learning-wise, an extremely unsatisfying semester.

Lectures confusing and unclear--it's his first semester teaching ME1. However he works very hard in studying the material and puts a lot of effort to help students. Great professor, but ME1 is not his specialty. Class organization is poor and disjunct, but machining lab is very fun. Midterms are inconsistent and tricky to study for.
A terrible teacher; although he is extremely interested in what he is teaching, his clarity is seriously lacking. He doesn't explain concepts well and expects you to learn them yourself.

He's adorable and can make boring topics seem at least remotely interesting. He loves to talk about his son (who is about 3 at the time of this comment). He's very patient, too. Kind of quiet but still funny. Only negative side was that he was extremely slow with grades, but that could just be because he was very busy this year.
I love this man. Take classes with him if you are looking for joyful and educational times.

Goldberg is an extremely nice teacher, who cares a lot about his students. He's also pretty funny, in a dorky linguistics/dad kind of way. Can sometimes be hard to understand, but if you make an effort to ask he's happy to clarify.
I felt like he wasn't that good of a lecturer and the material was kinda dry and boring but other people in my class really liked him so I don't know. Really sweet guy though.

He is super adorable and fun to listen to because he is so passionate about his subject.  Bring a computer to class so that you can pay attention / surf the web because he goes off on tangents a lot.  Easy to reach for office hours and really encourages class participation.  Generally an interesting class.

Kevin is the absolute best. He is incredibly intelligent, well-spoken, and has a wonderful sense of humor. He makes the Renaissance fun and is a joy to learn from. Plus he's hot, like your friend's dad.
Kevin is amazing! Friend talked me into taking his Shakespeare class and ended up being probably my favorite class of the semester.  Never a dull moment.

Such a G.  Take Shakespeare with him, he is hilarious.  I was a really great class, I learned a lot, was never bored, and never felt like I had an overwhelming amount of work.  It's pretty easy to get an A-.
Wonderful professor. interesting lectures, very clear and enthusiastic and funny. definitely take a class with him.
Great guy! Hilarious, and makes Shakespeare a joy to learn. If you take a Shakespeare class take it with him!

Fey is a really nice guy who loves to tell stories and go off on tangents during class. Lectures can be brutal at times and he is hard to contact outside class. Nonetheless, the material comes directly from the text, and he goes through each topic thoroughly, so if you're good at econ, you will well. A kind man, fair grader, solid professor

Definitely a very boring class, but the exams are what appears in the textbook. Although he grades relatively easily, he can be subjective in some cases. I think it's one of the easier classes in the department.

Literally reads from his slides word for word for the entire 75 minutes, stopping for an occasional anecdote that has zero relevance to the course material. Having said that, his tests are essentially the problem sets with some words shifted around, but they're graded relatively hard by the TA - class average is usually in the low 70's.

Do NOT attend Professor Fey's lectures. He drones on about the time he was consulting at AT&T in 12,000 BC and repeats the story every single lecture. Spend the time in the library reading the textbook, which his slides are word for word copied from.

Way better than all the bad things I have heard about him.  He does sit down in his chair and lecture through the slides, but he is very enthusiatic about the material.  So enthusiastic that he goes on tangents to make a specific point.
Worst Teacher I have ever had. Doesn't explain anything but expects you to know it all. Will go through slides on the board but not explain any of them. He's a bad teacher and a hard grader.

Easily the worst professor I've had at Tufts. Professor Fey shows no interest in teaching. He goes through about 5-10 powerpoint slides per chapter, skipping through them too quickly to write down any information, and the rest of the class consists of him discussing his personal theories. You'll be teaching yourself absolutely everything.

I took poetry with him and he was great. He's funny and makes the 3 hour block go by pretty fast. A lot of the girls in my class did not like him and I'm not sure why. He might have an arrogant undertone, but he's super nice to everyone. The class is easy and you just have to write poems weekly. There are sometimes short papers. He grades easy.

He's a nice, funny guy. I enjoyed the class even though 3 hours of poetry, any class really, can be rough. Class is mostly workshop. Mark doesn't expect much from your work so feel free to be as creative as you would like and try new things. Some thought he was stuck up, but I did not get that feel from him.
Chillest bro at this school. He's not the best poet, but an incredibly great poetry teacher. Take him.
Absolute Boss.  Just take his class if you can get into it.
Great class, great prof. Really cares about students and their understanding/progress. Will reward dedication and enthusiasm, was very helpful during office hours

Very fun class, and considering it's a three-hour class, it goes by pretty quickly. Mark was extremely friendly and approachable. Weekly workload consisted of readings (poems and short essays), critiquing classmates' poems, and writing your own.
Geraldine was one of the most open teachers I had. She was super caring, and also was a great teacher
Haha.. Just take her class, it's an experience........... Not as hard as Pfaffinger, but you may not learn as much as a result. She is absolutely fun-loving and I promise you you'll enjoy her class.

She's a riot. One of the funniestquirkiest professors I've ever had. Really smart and really helpful. Lectures can get boring sometimes, and she moves a bit quickly. That being said, if you ask her to slow down, she'll do so. Also love that she gives you applicable vocabulary. Words that you'd actually use in Germany as a college student.

I LOVE her. Genuinely cares about all students, so funny, nice, chill, and really knows her stuff. I can't say enough good things about her. Readings were interesting, not too much work (material itself a bit difficult but she's very understanding if you couldn't understand much of it or used translation help), and easy grader.

I cannot say enough good things about Geraldine.  People talk about how awesome she is, and she actually IS that awesome.  And you learn a lot and I mean A LOT of German.  And she teaches you relevant, everyday German--which was especially impressive when we read medieval German texts.  Literally just take a class with her.
She is the BEST!

Oh sweet Jesus Geraldine is incredible. She is so cool and forgiving. She teaches you a lot of slang ("What you really need to know in Germany"), and is so nice on tests and homeworks. You might not learn the most grammatical German possible, but it is so worth it. :)

AWESOME PROFESSOR. Constant skits, fun anecdotes that actually played into learning the language. She was simply the most enthusiastic person I have ever come across. Coming into the course, I really did not want to take German again, but she COMPLETELY changed that opinion. TAKE HER COURSE IF YOU HAVE THE CHANCE.
Geraldine is awesome! She is very casual and fun. Readings are interesting, and not too long. Essay assignments are often creative. Fun class.
Extremely helpful, very good at explaining concepts,etc, and genuinely cares about her students and their progress.  I would highly recommend taking a class with her.

Helpful in his office hours regarding the essay writing; However, the lecture itself oftentimes is bland and confusing. Especially for a philosophy class, he is unable to deliver information bit by bit and clarify concepts effectively. For the first part of the class his Powerpoint comes directly from the book and thus was not informative.

I took this class because I was interested in game theory from a non-econ perspective. The course material was really hard to digest and Prof. Forber's lectures are just directly from the chapters assigned for reading. No real effort is made to clarify for people without a game theory/math background and prof does not clarify well.

Forber isn't just one of the best professors I've had at Tufts, he's one of the best teachers I've ever had. He clearly explains complicated concepts, he has a passion for the material, and he makes students care about the material. He's a big reason I'm majoring in Philosophy, I can't recommend him highly enough.
Fails to explain hard concepts that are required to read. he thinks he explains well, however he simply confuses everybody.
Very passionate and refreshing.

Took the class for the finance minor, ended up really enjoying it. Course has 2 papers, 2 problem sets and a final exam. It seems like a really easy course at first, but you do need to work hard for a good grade. Not necessarily an easy A. Professor Forber's a great lecturer and tries to engage his students in a lot of fun ways.

Extremely intelligent and cares about the topic.  Very helpful, clear, approachable, and seems to know everything there is to know about the subject .  Probably one of the best professors I've had at Tufts--definitely the best I've had in the philosophy department.

Great Professor. Classes are very structured. Every time he goes over what the reading was about and outlines all the important information. Not a lot of discussion, but always answers any questions. Assignments are fair, but require effort to get an A. Overall a really approachable guy with one of the sharpest minds I've encountered at this school
Extremely engaging; a lot of class discussion/debate. Presented both sides of every problem; a lot of fun!

Great professor, during lecture he goes over what students were supposed to get from the reading and connects it to broader themes in the class. Assignments are fair, although not very engaging. Also very helpful and willing to explain things if you ask.

This class focuses on the textbook and supplementary readings. So, if you don't read, you won't pass. There are 3 papers and 2 tests. She talks a LOT and sometimes it seems in circles, but that's philosophy. The only complaint is she takes excessive time to grade, prepare to wait weeks.
Take notes of everything she says- Great teacher- Very helpful if you go for office hours. You'll do well

The class is really as easy or hard as you make it. You can get by without doing the majority of the readings because you don't have to participate in class. But her notes are really unclear and it seemed like her expectations on essays were unrealistic and certainly not well explained.
puts students head to head with philosophers. if you have any interest in philosophy, you will enjoy and learn.

Professor Urbanek is terrific! I came in expecting to enjoy Philosophy and she gave us great readings, while going over each text scrupulously in class. I loved the massive amounts of feedback she provides on papers. This is particularly helpful because you are allowed three rewrites. Take her course!

She is a great teacher who's really funny. Her notes on the board are really useful, especially when it explains arguments from readings. Her paper topics are interesting and it's obvious by her comments that she spends time grading your essay carefully. Her jokes in class make up for when the material is dry. It's a good introduction to philosophy

Valentina came late to class, then spent the next 5 to 10 minutes writing on the board.  she kind of went through the material and often put students to sleep.  there was class discussion, but only for the students she wanted to hear from, and if she didn't like you, you couldn't get an A.  take Philosophy 1, just not with her

This class was one of the worst decisions of my entire Tufts career. The lectures were interesting but were really a chance for the teacher to rant about random topics,& only about half the class was based on test material. A very low percentage of the class attended each class/got good grades. Horribe, I wish I could take it all back.

He makes everything he talks about interesting and is clear at the same time.  He really knows what he's talking about.  The work load is reasonable just as long as you don't wait until the last minute to do everything.  Very fair and interesting class.

GREAT PROFESSOR!!! One of the most coherent, knowledgeable and engaging lecturers I've ever had. He'll make you interested in things you never cared about. Workload isn't too bad (and he offers extra credit!), but he does make you work to get an A. TAKE THIS CLASS!!!

Class ranges from mildly interesting to incomprehensible. Tends to go off on unrelated tangents. Moderately difficult grader. Would not recommend taking this class unless you really need a world civ/art credit.

Great Professor! Very stimulating and knowledgeable. Fair grader, though requires extra effort to earn the A (if you want it). Really cool guy, get to know him after class. And TAKE A CLASS WITH HIM!!!
Scott is great - approachable, friendly, and a great lecturer who lays out his expectations for his students clearly. I would take another class with him, given the chance.

Writes a lot on the board, but it's all useful- I liked that he explained everything clearly and conceptually, but also did practice problems. really nice and approachable; I recommend going to his office hours.
Amazing at explaining things! Good handwriting, easy to follow in class
He's okay all around.
Best professor I've had - makes the material super interesting and is a very fair grader. Take Molecular Biology just to take his class!

Professor McVey is definitely one of the best professors I've ever had. He clearly cares so much about every one of his students and he's incredibly passionate about what he teaches. I found his BIO61 class to be very straight forward. There were two midterms, two papers, and a final group project. Very manageable and he's a wonderful human being.
Professor McVey teaches material in a straight forward manner. He is really easy to talk to and want his student to be successful. My favorite professor at Tufts!
The best ever
The best professor I've had at Tufts

McVey is the single best biology professor I've had at Tufts, and I think the Bio department at Tufts is overall is pretty strong. Helpful, kind, clear, and respectful of everyone. He encourages discussion, too, which makes the lectures more dynamic. Wish I could have taken Molecular Bio with him as well!

Very helpful. I took this class the first time he taught it and he was incredibly receptive to feedback, so we as the students were able to shape what we were learning and how we learned it. Very easy to talk to and really takes the time to make sure students understand what is going on. Readings were actually pretty helpful.

McVey is easily the best bio professor at Tufts. Bio of Aging was extremely interesting and (as far as major classes go) one of the most straightforward classes the department offers.
