Marci will not mince words. Her feedback has been invaluable to me; she has an incredible grasp of what works and what doesn't. I am a better writer thanks to her.

She knows what she wants to hear from students, so creativity seems to be ok but lowers your grade,which you don't know till you get it on your transcript. Instead of teaching, she enjoys reading stories and plays favorites. Fairness is not her strength, neither is creative writing! Not a good teacher.Take her if you don't care about your grade.
Worst teacher I've had at Tufts. Unfair grades, unprepared for class and horrible workshop style class.

She loves creative writing and is good at it. Her creativity is amazing, but she cannot convey it to her students. Her demands are not related to what she teaches and her end-of-the-semester-surprise grades have nothing to do with the body of writing produced, it's based on sympathy. Watch out!
Very fun class. Captivating stereotypical English professor. Wish there was more writing and less editing of other people's weird stories.
An intense class, but I learned a lot about writing.  She really knows what she's talking about, and is very helpful.
The assignments, games and stories we had in class were excellent in inspiring good writing.  Also, she was personally very encouraging and helpful.
Fun class!
Knowledgeable professor, well respected in his field of research. His class is hard, and he tries to cover too much material, but he teaches really well. Very flexible and understanding.

Professor Colvard is a nice man and a helpful professor. He held office hours and was quick to answer emails. He's a speedy lecturer which can make note taking hard but he always uploads the pdf slides later so it doesn't really matter. We had three exams which sometimes help oddly specific or broad questions. If you study the terms you'll do fine.

Would not recommend. This class is  based on lectures, which then are used to formulate the three exams (in addition to a group project and participation).  Though Professor Colvard is a caring individual, the structure of his class is conducive to a dull atmosphere. Dreadful group projects. No fun and wish I would have known. Time Machine, please?

If you're looking to fulfill a science distribution requirement, look elsewhere. Extremely dry lectures are followed by exams that are more about rote memorization than actual learning. The group project isn't terribly difficult, but it was more time-intensive than I expected it to be. Overall, this class is doable but disappointing.

Absolutely terrible professor. Exams are heavily based on obscure facts from his poorly written lecture slides. Wildly inconsistent exams- my grade on exam 1 was an A and my grade on the second was a D. Many lecture slides are lifted word for word from Wikipedia. Unless you have your heart set on environmental studies- don't take this class.

Dry, uninspirational. The "learning" is very facts based (i.e.: no learning, not connected). He doesn't back up a lot of the things he says, leaving me to question some of the very arbitrary categories that we need to know, e.g.: there are 5 "something something" (e.g: pollutants), and there 3 sources of pollution. Sad, sad, class :(

Zarin led a trip to Uganda, where she delivered nightly lectures on evolutionary biology, with emphasis on apes. She is a master professor. She is leading researcher in the world on the topic. Yet, she can explain difficult concepts and voluminous articles with simplicity. I will be sneaking into her lectures at Tufts as often as possible.
She's amazing. Take any class with her. Stunning human.

Zarin is not only an amazing human, but also an amazing professor. I learned so much from her. The tests are really just memorizing the slides, so if you're good at memorization and willing to put in work the class is managable. Her office hours are also great for clarifying class or life questions

One of the best professors I've had at Tufts. Prof Machanda is so brilliant, kind, and excited to get to know all of her students. This was one of the harder classes I've taken but I really enjoyed it.

She is an amazing professor and at the top of her field. She brings her knowledge of fieldwork to the class, along with photos, videos and first hand expertise. The exams are difficult, so study like crazy. She cares about her students and is a true gem. This was her first semester at Tufts and Tufts is lucky to have her.

She's super accessible and hands down one of the best people and professors I've ever met. The class is more a 3.5 on difficulty scale and will probably become easier in the years to come. Highly recommend taking this!

I loved this class!!! She organized the information very well, and all her lectures were very engaging, but the workload was pretty high. Nevertheless, I would still take this course again with her if I could!
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Gives good feedback', 'Participation matters']

rComments: One of the best professors I've ever had. She is so smart, caring, and a great teacher. The class is amazing, but be prepare to deal with material that can be emotionally overwhelming (migrants, etc.). Fantastic lectures, and she leaves lots of time for discussion and makes sure everyone is included. I love Prof. El-Khoury!

El-Khoury's class on Paris is amazing. You learn a lot about contemporary issues, but the class is also a lot of fun. She obviously loves Paris and it is communicative. Great class if you want to consolidate your grammar but go beyond a language class. She rewards creativity a lot (but is also very caring about your progress in grammar)
I learned so much about the reality of today's world, and the humanity behind the political conflicts, from all perspectives. I love her classes. She is sincerely the best professor I have ever had.

I took French Culture with Prof. El Khoury last semester, and it was amazing so I decided to take her Mediterranean Crossings Lit & Film class:  it was incredible. The readings and films are fascinating, and her lectures + class discussions are so stimulating. She is a fair grader, and is accessible out of class. I love Prof. El Khoury.

Best prof. I've ever had! Prof. El Khoury is such a good teacher and she is truly inspirational. She is extremely knowledgeable and caring. Her lectures are fascinating, and she gives a lot of time for discussion. Makes you rewrite your essays if they are not good. I would take this class again, and I will take other classes with her!
Very approachable and very considerate to students. Topics are interesting and engaging. Encourage and engage students. Very good course to take!
Scully is a tough grader, but gives great feedback. You'll be writing better by the end of the semester. Very helpful and wants his students to improve. :)

Matthew Scully is a smart guy with an interesting perspective. Workload isn't bad, but he does expect a very high level of writing from day 1, and I wouldn't take his class if you are looking to improve on writing while getting  a good grade. He does give a lot of feedback but he definitely is too harsh on his grading policies.

Nothing special for an English 1 class. Readings were pretty interesting, ranged from Ta Nehisi Coates to graphic novels. Class time itself though can be very boring, and discussions very stagnant. He gives really great advice on how to direct and improve your writing though, really makes you think.

Professor Levine is awesome and moderates great discussions. He infrequently teachers classes, but he is super smart (a Rhodes Scholar). He is also a very fair grader and is willing to give you help if you ask for it. If you get the chance to take a course with him, I would highly recommend it.

Luke's English 1 class definitely helped me improve my writing quite a bit. He's nice, and his feedback on papers has been very helpful for revising, but don't sleep on the fact that both my review and the first one used the "tough grader" tag, because he definitely is.

He doesn't give As because Tufts policy states that if you get an A in English 1, you don't have to take English 2. Other than that, he's a great guy, really laid-back. Always open to talk after class, his comments are helpful for revisions. He's leaving Tufts this semester for Bentley, I think. Very good at teaching you how to conduct research.
great prof

Totally boring class but Camara is really a talented lecturer. Beyond just being really intelligent, it takes a special kind of skill to put together a lecture that people will be able to listen to for an hour and fifteen minutes.  You can tell that she really cares about her students' progress and is always available for help.  Nice lady.
I find her to be extremely interesting.  She is sweet and entertaining, making you want to go to class.
she teaches out of the book but clarifies a lot of things...has structure to her teaching.  very good!
No Comments
Really sweet woman, but class is not worth going to. It's all straight out of the book. Easy A.
She is very nice but her class is very boring!!!
She's so nice! Class is interesting.
This man is, to put it politely, awful.

Good professor with interesting discussions. Keeps the entire class engaged. Some of the books we read weren't my favorite, but that's life. Essays were fairly graded, lots of topics to write about. Litvak is very passionate and has lots of interesting things to say. Tough class, kept you working and thinking hard, but rewarding.

i thought this dude was awesome. great ideas and great reading material, alot of stuff i never would have picked up myself. papers and exam easy, so you can actually concentrate on interpretation. lots of good****, **** and vag talk, on an intelectual level of course

Great up until the final, which promises to be based on 0% analysis or understanding of "Black Comedy" and 100% on memorization. An overlong, overweighted reading quiz. Great material though, and a pretty good lecturer.

Previous classes I have taken with Litvak were interesting and intellectually stimulating; however, his foray into politics leaves much to be desired.  He has a clear agenda in teaching this class and presents a very close-minded approach to the material.  He expects students to mimic his views with little room for student interpretation.

Worst professor I've had at Tufts.  Closed-minded and intolerant.  Judgmental and condescending.  If you have any interest in thinking for yourself are participating in enlightened in-class debates/discussions, do not take a course with him.
Hilarious and interesting, but not what you'd call open-minded. Likes to hear students echo his own thoughts back to him. Still highly engaging.
Best professor! Loves teaching. Self-depricating and hilarious.

Quizzes were a pain in the neck, and so was "that guy" who always raised his hand to let us know what he thinks about the material. I'd like the class better if the teacher made the students shut up and just told us what he thought.

very smart and humorous, however, this is lost in his interpretation of material (novels, films etc.). I felt like I was suppose to be a college professor instead of a college student in order to keep up in his class.
Patient, brillant, encouraging
A great teacher, kept me interested in a topic I had no interest in whatsoever.
Prof. Litvak is a cool guy.  Makes everything very interesting - he's funny too...and he looks like Kevin Spacey!
very good.  i agree though, very professional. i was intimidated.
A great lecturer. Personable and clear. Very professional.
Adorable
Tanya is very reasonable and helpful. She is not out to get you

Oh lord Tanya is literally the coolest. She is so kind, really cares about her students' understanding, and goes out of her way to make sure everyone does well in the class. Learned so much Russian. Ochen haroshiy prafessor!
Boring, unclear, and the class is too easy and very repetitious. Avoid if possible, though it's hard because she is the only who teaches it!
Tanya is the most amazing professor and human being!  She explains everything thoroguhly, is extremely approachable, and really tries and succeeds at helping students.
Tanya is the most amazing teacher in the Russian Department (which is quite the feat since that whole department is amazing) and any class with her will teach you a lot and be really fun too :)
Great. Really cool professor/ great personality. and extremely knowledgeable.

This woman is INCREDIBLE. Fantastic teacher, extremely interesting and clear, doesn't mind at all if your grasp of the language isn't so good, she's very patient. The subject matter is fascinating - she's not demanding at all, either, with just a few simple assignments, and is very eager to help. Definitely take it, SUCH a good teacher!

Best prof I've ever had. Really helpful outside of class and genuinely cares about the stories you submit. Wants you to succeed and will help you do so if you put in the time and effort. Can't recommend advanced fiction writing highly enough

Modern Mind will make you think about the world and yourself like you never have before, and I adored it. He's an easy grader on essays (there are 2), and the essays can be about anything at all that relates. There's one pretty unimportant quiz on the stuff he covers in class. No power points; he just talks at you the whole class, so pay attention!

Professor Cantor is the best teacher I've ever had. He fits my vision of what a professor should be. Places the emphasis on learning, lets the material speak for itself, and allows the class to engage. Doesn't focus on petty details, looks to see if students actually learned. lectures are like great stories. The material changed my outlook on life.

I can' tell if he's being ironic and trying to fight against the conventional system of schooling/grades, or just doesn't care at all. Example: He forgot to print out enough final exams so our class got automatic 100%. Either way though, his lectures always get to you think differently about the world. This class was different, but worth taking.

His Modern Mind class was fantastic for learning about Marx, Freud, and Nietszche. Only 1 paper as any kind of work all semester, but it's a bear. Turns out he doesn't even read/grade them unless you ask for feedback. Disappointing. Still, phenomenal class to take for a rambling genius to enlighten you on some of the great thinkers

He's down to earth, has a sense of humor and shows the students he's a human being outside of academia.  This is what a professor should be.  The workload was manageable and provided some flexibility, allowing for creativity within the realm of the assignments.  Some people cannot handle independence. If you can't, don't take the class.

I knew from the second I didn't laugh at one of his jokes, but the rest of the class was peeing themselves, that I would be alone in hating this class.  I never felt that he tried to include others in discussion.  I never felt he cared about getting to know the class.  But everyone else seems to worship the ground he walks on, so what do I know.

Prof Cantor offered many interesting ideas, but he is not very open to the ideas and opinions of others, especially if they differ from his.  He is funny and amusing at times, but his teaching style leaves much to be desired.
Thoroughly wonderful.

Cantor is eccentric, sporadic, and overly wonderful. He is very willing to engage students in an effort to develop their writing and thinking skills. He is clearly a master of his subjects, and is funny and kind to boot. Take his class; laugh at his jokes
Not the most logical teacher, but very entertaining and incredibly smart. His class leaves you thinking for the rest of the day.
One of the most passionate and inspirational teachers I've ever had.  Read his books- they're funny!
He is intelligent and engaging, and his randomness will definitely keep you entertained!
he is so irrational
Brilliant, hilarious, a great character.
a very witty man
He's like Woody Allen, but in a good way.  I'd take any class that he taught.

Very willing to help however difficult to understand.  Not especially careful about the accuracy of equations put on the board.  The book will be your Friend.  Only 1 test at end of semester and its worth 60% of final grade.  Yikes! Does not give A's.
he is a smart guy, but is a very hard grader. you have to work extra hard to pass his classes...
Discussions were not helpful and so was the professor

The most interesting, brilliant, and entertaining professor I've had at Tufts. I felt a personal responsibility to do the work for this class just because he was so cool! If you take a class with him, you can't go wrong.
This was my favorite class this semester, and I loved Prof. Wilson.  He was so funny, and class was so entertaining.  He is now my advisor.
Great teacher, even better person.  Take any class he's teaching
This guy rules.
He is hilarious, and a great teacher. I took a creative writing class of his and it was one of the best classes I ever took.
i honestly spent more than one class of his laughing until i was crying...wilson's great, and to top it off, he's british.
my favorite professor!
his classes will keep you laughing and interested. very cool guy.
he is the best

I took Spanish 21 and 22 with profe LK. At first, I didn't really care for her. But, when I went to her office hours for feedback, that made ALL the difference. She became my favorite professor at Tufts by the end of two semesters!! Sweetest woman and so funny!
Dont get on her bad side and you'll be all set. The typical busy work but theres a variety of things that get grades (tests, essays, projects, presentations, quizzes, homework, discussions etc)
teacherRatingTags: ['Gives good feedback', 'Clear grading criteria', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: I've had conflicting feelings about her since my first day of class. She's my only teacher at Tufts who can leave the room while her students are working, and the students remain silent and studious. All of her students have a lot of respect for her, however she can sometimes be too harsh. Tough grader, but very passionate.
She's professional and intelligent,  so sweet and lively (and lovely), cares about her students .
Sweetest, most helpful professor ever

Professor Levy-Konesky is a solid Spanish teacher.  Spn-0021 is a mix of grammar review and discussioncomprehension of some Spanish literature, both of which she teaches well.  Grades are from participation, 5 quizzes, 4 tests, 3 TV-show reviews, and 3 compositions.  If you put in effort & act on feedback, you will do well. Definitely recommend!!

She is a tough grader, and takes her job more seriously than some of the other Spanish Department Professors. She also seems to play favorites a bit with students. She also likes to call on students randomly. If you do the work you will be fine.

She is a fantastic teacher who truly wants her students to succeed! She may seem a little stern on her exterior, but she is very friendly and approachable. Every so often she randomly brings Puerto Rican snacks or candy to class! She is an easy grader, but her assignments still require some hard work - nothing extreme.

After the first test, I was scared that L-K will be a hard grader, but everything turned out ok. She is very enthusiastic and her classes are usually pretty interesting. She incorporates her own handouts and videos into the course. Most importantly, she gives out candy/chocolate on test days!

she is probably one of the best language teacher's i have had. she not too tough when it comes to grading compositions and exams, which makes me like her even more. def recommend taking a class with her

She is one of my favorite teachers I've at at Tufts so far. She is incredibly enthusiastic and funny and makes class go by fast. She is a pretty easy grader on compositions and tests and such a nice person. Definitely suggest taking a class with her!

Nancy Levy-Konesky is an amazing Spanish teacher. She's really enthusiastic and loves her students - even gives chocolates during exams. She's adorable and great at explaining things. She really fosters class participation and makes even the apathetic students want to get involved. I would absolutely take another class with her.

I felt awkward asking questions: if she thinks it's a stupid question she gets frustrated and sarcastic, making it very uncomfortable.  I'm not the strongest Spanish student, and she would get impatient with me easily.  She knows her stuff, but I hated going to class.
Excellent

column1: One of very few bright lights in the Tufts Community.

rComments: she is absolutely, bar none, the best language professor i have ever had. she is extremely helpful, and always makes the classes interesting when you don't think it would be possible. DEFINITELY TAKE A CLASS WITH NANCY IF YOU GET A CHANCE!
She is definately the BEST spanish teacher I've had at tufts so far, she is very interested in her students progress and has lax deadlines. I have learned alot in this class.
Nancy is the best spanish teacher I've ever had.  She's extremely lively, entertaining, sweet, and helpful.  I learned a lot without working too hard.  And she definitely cares for each student.
She treated her students as if they were her own children.  I looked forward to going to her classes.
Not patient with students who are struggling

Professor Johnson was my favorite Russian teacher at Tufts. Her method of teaching through discussion and partner work helped me improve my Russian more than I thought was possible and I became more confident in my skills as a result. She really cares about helping students understand and learn the language. I wish Vida taught all Russian classes.

Wonderful woman.  Knows an incredible amount about the subject matter, has written lots of published work about it and knows many of the people who directed/produced/starred in the films she screens.  However, if you're not interested in the topic you might find yourself bored in the class sometimes.  Overall, great teacher.
Vida is the best! TAKE HER CLASS. You will learn so much, eat animal crackers and wish she was your very own sweet Slavic grandmother

Prof. Johnson is very nice as long as you come to class. She brings snacks every day, and she has a ridiculous amount of knowledge on the subject so I learned a lot. Lots of great films, some not so good, but great class overall. You have to keep a film journal and write a paper for the midterm. The textbook (Understanding Movies) is not necessary.

Vida is amazing take her Russian Film course and have a great time discussing movies you will most likely be viewing for the first time. Very interesting and Vida always has something worthwhile to add without stifling the class discussion...

Andres has a different way of teaching. Do not expect to be spoon-fed the exam material. His lectures are simply a hazy image of what the test will be like. Your job is to understand everything he discusses and fill in the blanks by reading the text-book on your own. With that said, he is an incredible professor--passionate and brilliant.

BU CGS Natural Science professor. Possibly worst professor I have ever had. He doesn't explain anything, he is condescending and confusing. Doesn't answer questions well and gives assignments that don't make sense and he doesn't even check them. DO NOT TAKE HIM.
Knows his sabermetrics, class was great.  Andres distracted sometimes, but into sabermetrics for sure and knows his stuff...
Baseball in the spring at Tufts -- Andres has put together a great class.  Bill James came to talk with us!
Great class -- baseball for credit!!  Andres is great and knows his stuff too.
Awesome class, baseball analysis for credit!  Andres was great, knows his stuff...

Teaches Sabermetrics: Baseball Statistical Analysis for Ex-College.  Andy and the assistant teachers are really cool, and know tons about baseball and stats.  Take this course if you're any good at math and like to talk about baseball.

Professor Kanarek is a caring and knowledgeable person who does not have or no longer has a flair for lecturing. She recites material blandly out of the textbook and does not maintain an inclusive classroom. She gave us a project once to "pretend we were poor and had to use food stamps" and to write down how it felt. Also very hard to email.
Eh

So intelligent and successful, really knows her stuff. She's SO chill and just wants you to learn and as long as you're interested in the topic and a good student, you'll get an A. Lots of papers every week but you can just skim them or read the abstract. No tests at all, just a final project that wasn't too terrible. Class was super interesting

She's a bit scatterbrained but overall a good professor. She's not that harsh when it comes to grading, and attempts to let students pursue their interests. However, she tended to cover material a bit shallowly, leaving me under-prepared for upper levels
she deserves 12 chili peppers.
She is an understanding and caring teacher.  One of the best I've had at Tufts.  She is brilliant.  Take any class you can with her.
No Comments
Professor Zhong inspired me to become a film major. This class and the films we watched were a thorough revelation, even though the films were sometimes quite hard to watch. But you won't regret it.

I thoroughly enjoyed her class. The films were mostly interesting, and even when they weren't, the analysis lecture gave them new meaning. It isn't a ton of work, you just have to be diligent and use your time wisely when you're watching the films so you have enough insight to write the weekly response. The professor always kept convos interesting.

She is average at best. I took a film class with her a few semester back and the class is mostly watching film plus writing a really long responses every week. Lots of readings. Lectures are her rambling off . And her grading is extremely uninformative. She always said good, but the course grade turned out what you did not expect from the feedbacks

If you're going to take a class with Zhong LaoShi, make it a film class.  I enjoyed her fim choices for the most part in Chinese Film, but now in Youth and Culture in Modern China I am unimpressed.  The lectures are repetitive and rambling, making it hard to want to do the readings.  Lots about this class falls short.
Really great professor. I really enjoyed this class and think of the films often. She is obviously very intelligent and very willing to help you outside class.

Great teacher! Class very informative and interesting even for non-film people. Films do get kind of long, however. Few graded assignments but fair grading. I very much enjoyed this class and teacher.

Class time alternates between screening and lecture days.  Lecture days could be exhausting but were valuable.  The films were excellent, the readings interesting if underused, and the professor had interesting comments and encouraged class participation.  Not the best class but I enjoyed it.  Don't take if you don't really enjoy discussing film.

she knows her stuff, for sure, but is not very open to other views especially if you're an amateur at analyzing films. the films get better as the semester progresses, but she assigns way too many readings. there's a required film response to every movie we watch and three 5-page papers.

Brilliant mind, somewhat wandering lectures. For me, I like organization--especially when grappling with complex ideas like philosophy and Confucianism! So, I appreciate her brilliance and williness to challenge students, but found lectures very hard to follow.
Assigns too many readings that are never discussed in class.  Lectures had almost nothing to do with the films and were three hours long.  Her grading is also pretty random.

This was a pretty awful class. The movies she chose were boring, we read essays written by her, and she gave unclear and usually had very few valuable points in her lectures. The workload was light and it didn't require too much brainwork. I would fall asleep multiple times in one class, and when I was awake I saw other people sleeping. . .

He doesn't overload you with work, but his feedback is nevertheless really useful if you have an interest in writing. If you put in an effort with your writing, it will be reflected in your grade, even if you're new to it. The class is good for the soul. Definitely do it.

Awesome professor. Joe clearly cares a lot about his students, and he doesn't overload you with too much work. You'll get better at writing, and you'll probably feel emotionally/spiritually lifted coming out of his class.

What an amazing guy! Prof. Hurka is a rare gem- gives such great feedback, very respective and inclusive of different writing backgrounds and styles, and if you don't take his course for that, take it for his amazing anecdotes and guitar skills.

I took J. Hurka over summer for Fictional Writing. It was my first fictional writing course. I learned so much about writing, analyzing and critiquing. He is a true gem at Tufts University and truly cares about his students in and out of class. He is very well connected within the writing community. A must take course, you won't be disappointed.

Joe's the best professor I've had so far at Tufts. He genuinely cares about his students and their works, takes an interest in students' life and tries to help them in as many ways as possible. His class always makes my day. And two and half hours feel too short.

Joe was a fantastic teacher. Always ready to help, and mesmerizing with his personal stories. Highly knowledgeable and constructive, while being very open to all suggestions. This chili's for you, Joe!!

Hurka was awesome. Definitely ask him to bring in his guitar if he doesn't offer anyways. I wish I took more initiative to meet with him, because you really get the feeling he will remember you forever. He's the best basically.

Had Hurka in his last class at Emerson, one of the best writing professors and one of the best people I've had the pleasure of knowing. Serious, emotional, light-hearted guy who really cares about his students and their futures. You won't regret taking a class with him.
Hurka is an awesome professor. His short stories are fantastic. He really guides you. Google him.
Everyone else has pretty much said it. Joe is a wonderful professor. He really cares about helping students improve their writing. Very nice, funny guy too.

Encourages students to call him Uncle Joe.  Down to earth amazing professor with so much to share.  Doing work for his class is fun, not work.  Take this guys class...if you can get in.  Everyone loves Uncle Joe.
Awesome

Joe is hands-down my all-time favorite professor.  He not only is engaging and intelligent, but he's a writer that deeply cares about passing on his love of writing and literature to others.  Take a class with him.  You will never regret it.
three years out of tufts, but never forget joe hurka...still talk to him...take this man's class...he inspires

Best class (and professor) I have ever had.  This class kept me going through the semester; I looked forward to it every week.  Really comfortable atmosphere, allowed to take chances with your writing, Joe is always there to help, so inspirational, never an emphasis on grades.  I can't say enough good things.  Loved every minute of class time.

Ok, I am eight years out of Tufts, but I still remember Joe Hurka's story about a dog that humped his leg and would. not. stop.  Hilarious.  Oh, and he was also a good professor.  Engaged and engaging.
Joe is the man. His stories and experiences are really interesting. He is an actual writer and takes part in many of the in class excercises himself, genuinely interested in his students.

Uncle Joe is the best; his class was my favorite out of all my classes at Tufts yet. He's a very understanding, warm, fun guy who teaches fiction writing with a passion. He's also a great guitarist and a wonderful listener.
Really amazing. One of the best professors/people at Tufts. Take a class with him before you leave.
Fantastic Guy! A truly great/hot teacher!
Uncle Joe is the most fun English teacher I've ever had, and he really knows good writing.
No Comments

This man is my hero.  He will gladly become your friend and mentor if you so desire.  His classes are always light and humorous and this man knows how to write fiction and to teach it.  Take him if possible.
No Comments
Go, Uncle Joe
Uncle Joe was the best!
Awesome guy, understanding, fun class and good papers. Just about everything you need to do well. Easy to do well with a little effort, I'd recommend him to anyone

He was an amazing professor. Previous comments say that he didn't hand papers back on time, but he always gave our papers back about a week after we turned them in. He is suepr chill and has real deep thoughts. His materials were really interesting. Definitely take him for English 2!!!

My god he's the easiest teacher at Tufts. I am serious, it feels literally like a 5th grade class, where you sit back and just relax. If you ever have a question on a paper, he pretty much offers you an extension! He says something along the lines of..."yeah..so uh..do it whenever, and give it to me when you are ready."

Brian is the man. you don't need to buy a single book for his class. any reading you have (short stories) he gets copies and hands them out. Yeah, it takes a while for him to hand back essays, but he eventually does. He is also VERY lenient with extensions and the like. he's a very chill, down to earth guy.

Wicked cool guy but...hands back papers really late.  Always willing to give extensions and is really good about meeting w/ people for extra help.  I totally reccomend him, but only if you are willing to not really learn anything new and just have a fun class...I mean it is just Eng 2

Sooooo nice. We had many varying assignments and read an interesting book, called Blink. Basically, he held class twice a week and then had individual writing meetings the third day. It was very helpful. We would always have a draft due and then the final paper. It usually took a while to get our papers back but oh well.

The class was such a waste of time.  I didn't learn anything.  He never gives any papers back, so it's hard to know if your doing well or not.  At least he was available for outside help...accept when you asked if he had graded any of your papers yet.

Brian is so wonderful.  His class is fun and laid back, but it's obvious he knows what he's talking about, and he encourages his students to challenge themselves.  He is very accessible and helpful, and his writing assignments are nicely varied.  Good class considering it is intro level.

I loved this class! Swafford's a great guy who is really knowledgeable about film and writing; he always has great feedback and ready to help. Lectures are pretty laid back, funny, and exciting if you get into the topic. Was a pleasure getting to know him. As long as you show up to lectures and do the work, the class is pretty straight forward.

He's pretty lenient about late assignments.  Most classes are discussionlecture, occasional essay workshops (very important to be there with a complete rough draft), plus the film screenings.  He only comes to about half of those, so you can get away with not going to them.  Be warned that writing for film is different than analyzing literature.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Get ready to read']

rComments: I loved this class, it's worth waking up early for! Because he is a well-versed writer and has a lot of experience (has written a few books, writes for Slate), we've learned to read pieces with a more criticalappreciative perspective. The class is pretty chill and he does a good job of giving great feedback.

A lot of the work feels like busy work, and class at 8:05 in the morning is never awesome, but he will help you pull straight through this class, and he's always ready to help with getting you a good essay grade.  Really, while I did not enjoy the class, the class is a must-take since it walks you through college writing.
He is a great guy that really knows his stuff. He grades fairly and is very helpful at office hours. Definitely helped me become a better writer

Did not enjoy this class, he's a very unorganized and boring professor.  Very knowledgeable about film however.  My advice: make sure you are 100% interested in the subject before taking. Disaster of a class if you don't like the material.

He's unorganized and seems like there is no point to go to class b/c we aren't tested on lectures, but he's very knowledgable with film. The only work is papers and you chose your topic, so it depends how interested you are in a paper that can make it fun. He is a great guy to get to know and a very good writer. If you like films I highly recommend
Completly scattered and unoranized.  class is way too boring.  grading is arbitrary.  paper topics dull.  dreaded the class.
Not taught very well for such an important class. Too much of the work was handed out to the TA's

Pfeifer's a nice guy- the problem was that he DIDN'T TEACH. He didn't always come to class, and when he did, gave a convoluted lecture and ended early. The TA's tried- but overall, did not learn anything. The class material wasn't hard, but was presented in over-complicated ways and graded ridiculously. I hear Pfeifer won't be around much longer.

Agree with what most people have said. Very nice, passionate about the field, wants his students to do well. However, the lectures are pretty useless, the problem sets are very hard, and the grading is hugely unpredictable. Could not be happier that this course is ending.

He's pretty bad compared to some of the other professors I have had at Tufts. You would think that a professor here wouldnt have any problems with public speaking, but you can tell he is really nervous and I think it hindered class learning. Generally, I felt that this class moved too slow, mainly because his explanations are extremely wordy.

Ok so he's not the best in the department, but he's certainly pretty good. He can be confusing at times and you don't really understand thermo after this class, but hey, thermo is hard. He makes a huge effort, always available, very organized, really nice and he's very biologically oriented. Problem sets usually take 10-12 hours.

He is so bad as the teacher. It is unbelievable that he have no idea about what he taught. compared with other professors in the department, he did not taught you. so try to avoid him. take others class,especially for thermodynamics. recommend professor jerry meldon.

Professor Pfeifer is nice enough but that doesn't cut it when it comes to teaching thermodynamics.  I never felt like the material was actually "taught".  During class he would go through long, complicated examples that just confused everyone.  I have had to go back and learn the fundamentals of thermo for later classes.

He wants to please the class, but is very bad at teaching the material in class.  He does problems the entire time but in such a way that you do not get anything out of them.  Most boring class ever - hopefully he will get better as he gains experience.
Nice guy, quite hip. Not the best teacher though. Has potential. Too new when we took this class.
Good professor, pleasant, explains well, and knows the subject matter. His Radar Engineering course is highly recommended.
Very easygoing guy, and definitely a Subject Matter Expert
from industry, knows what he's talking about, and imparts it to students with no problem. very sympathetic to working students
Prof. Paradis rocks.  Very well prepared, extremely helpful, exams relevant and reflect the material studied.  A fair graded.  Enjoyed his class a ton!
Great professor! Understanding and willing to help you understand how this applies to your job or future job.
Nice guy, well educated and wants his students to learn. His classes can be a little bit boaring, but he is a fair and easy grader...
Nice guy. His lectures are not academically intense, but he knows his stuff. More into real-world applications. He is from industry, so his classes have this flavor.
Amazing instructor.  Changed the way I do nutrition.
No Comments
No Comments
No Comments

LOVEDDD Cathy and this class. Such a cool combo of anthropology/science topics regarding our American food systems. We have 3 big projects and 1 exam. Readings due for each class to help facilitate the discussions. Low-stress but she grades harder than you'd think.

Lots of reading, and transcriptions are just annoying. But we got to travel to Boston Public Market, and she is so kind, flexible and understanding. She wants everyone to do well, and truly listens. Very intelligent, too!

First Anthro class taken at Tufts, really enjoyed it, good intro, provides nice general landscape of the field especially through the lens of Global Cities, which I think is very relate-able to most students. Reading load generally acceptable, sometimes a little bit more than I'd like, but overall decent. Super nice and rather helpful teacher.
Attendance isn't mandatory, but is very helpful for understanding concepts. Three papers and one final test.

Global Cities is great if you love cities/urbanism & anthro (yes, both), but probably a little wonky if you don't. Stanton is an extremely nice person and a reasonably effective professor, and the grading is really not that hard. Only complaint is that occasionally the subject matter veered away from anthro into overly leftist political discussion.

Professor Stanton is one of the nicest professors I've had at Tufts. While the course itself was required and therefore not overly interesting, she did her best to engage us in the theory. Very approachable and overall a great woman.
The word mediocrity comes to mind. She is a great person, and an interesting conversationalist, but as a professor, mediocre.
I did not enjoy this course much. The lectures and readings are boring and don't really relate to the assignments (though you're expected to reference them in the papers).

she's a really boring teacher. all of her classes this semester were 90% lecture, and we sometimes watch clips of movies but that's pretty rare. the reading for class is extremely boring. so i rely on taking notes during lecture instead of actually finishing the readings.

pretty easy, pretty boring, has quiet voice and its a big class so hard to stay awake sometimes..she means well and knows her stuff but lectures on and on- the quizzes are straight forward and you dont have to do the reading, just memorize a bunch of terms. overview of religions.

Professor Meister is a great professor. I truly enjoyed her class. Additionally, she is extremely knowledgeable about the subject. I definitely recommend taking this class.

Mrs. Meister really brought the subject matter alive.  She is passionate about her field, and clearly very knowledgeable.  If you seek her out, she will go above and beyond to help you. Professor Meister was great, lectures were engaging and the material fascinating.   If you seek out her help she will spend time and energy helping you to succeed in her class.

Prof. Smith is so so so kind. She will warm your heart with every lecture. She is a real gem and genuinely cares about each of her students. I was lucky to learn from her. Take her Spanish Civil War class if you can. It is very interesting and pretty easy too!

-Prof. Smith cares about student involvement and understanding. She shares antecdotes from her  time in Latin America, and it makes for a relatable classroom experience! She is a great teacher. She cares about the success of her students and is a pretty easy grader. I highly recommend her class.
She is an awesome teacher who really cares about the success of her students. I highly recommend her class.

Profa Smith is literally the cutest person in the whole world. If you can past the the time-consuming workload, this class is actually really interesting. He only gives about 5 or 6 homework assignments, but make sure you start them early because they take awhile to finish.

fun, engaging - keeps lectures interesting. better than most other ENP and HF profs who can be boring and dry and get stuck on certain topics like air traffic control over and over and over again. material not very exciting but at least you get to choose your own materials in advanced class. always on email. like always, really.

sommers is the man. super engaging, does lots of little experiments in the middle of lectures which are usually hilarious, and explains things really well with examples and analogies. he might not be the visual learner's cup of tea (his slides are god-awful) but the textbook is a great supplement to the lectures, probably because he wrote it.

He's so funny and very engaging, but his tests are fairly difficult and can be very laborious and the grading can be very nitpicky for both papers and exams. He made learning research methods interesting, but I would recommend taking the class with a different instructor instead
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', 'Lots of homework', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

Sam Sommers is the best proffesor out of the three you have for this class. He makes the class interesting my using a variety of sources (videos, games) he is also very confident, and therefore clear when he speaks. GO SAM SOMMERS!

he's great! everyone loves him.

Wonderful professor, such an interesting class. I look forward to it every week. He's humorous and manages to make everything extremely interesting. Try to take this class if any way possible, you won't regret it. Plus he's adorable.

i work in sommers' psych lab doing research, i'm only speaking on that aspect of his skill: he's a great advisor and a wonderful asset/ he helps with understanding research. <3 him. great professor, wonderful person.
psych and law is a great class. extremely interesting and sommers is hilarious.

Great conductor. Funny guy.

Wang laoshi is probably the best professor I've had at Tufts so far. He made you want to come to class everyday and ready to learn new material, even if the course was intensive. He made class pretty entertaining and is always willing to help you out, he wants to see you succeed.

Wang laoshi is my favorite Chinese teacher. Not only is he easy to understand, and very clear in his expectations, but he is likable, friendly, and extremely funny. Wang Laoshi is awesome and super super nice. He's always willing to let you take quizzes or pass in homework later and he knows that Intensive Chinese is a tough workload. He really wants to see you do well and it's not hard at all to get an A b/c he's not a hard grader. take Intensive!!
He is extremely helpful and nice and really wants you to do well
wang laoshi is an amazing teacher!!! take his class!

The best language professor I've ever had.  Extremely approachable, helpful, and funny, Prof. Wang makes learning Chinese interesting and entertaining.  Like someone said earlier, I would love to have him as an uncle!

What a wonderful man! I wish he were my uncle. He makes learning Chinese super engaging and knows a ridiculous amount about languages overall. He asks for a lot but is very understanding about grades and assignments. V accessible outside of the classroom! I LOVE HIM! You will too!
wonderful

best language teacher i've ever had. he has an incredible command of languages and their workings (esp english!). funny guy, helpful, organized. i never dread going to this class. an essential contact if you want to pursue paths relating to china. great guy, nothing but good things to say about him.

Awesome man and makes jokes so strange that you can't help but laugh. I probably laugh more in this class than any other. Very helpful and understanding, full of suggestions and helpful comments. Probably the best language teacher I've ever had.

Very nice teacher and also very good. Very funny and entertaining. Makes class fun besides teaching chinese.
he's a super nice guy... very understanding, clear, and helpful.

she is so nice, almost too nice to the point where kids take advantage of her. she is very encouraging, and everything is "bueno."

Hava is the nicest, most caring, most qualified and sweetest language professor at Tufts (and known outside as well). She is very concerned with her students' progress and teaches very well. She is pretty and cute, a little motherly (in the good way), and very fun to take.

This is a pretty good class.  The work and tests were easy and the teacher is very helpful and just wants everyone to do well.  She's also supposedly much better than the other Hebrew 1 teacher. If you are taking this class, take it with this professor.

Also, the overall setup of the course is careless and the textbook is extremely unclear, unhelpful, and overpriced.

Excellent professor. Really nice guy. Very helpful. I can't say enough about Afsar. Take him for ES 3!! While you can expect to be completely lost for the first few weeks, eventually, it'll all make sense. And if it doesn't, he'll give you an "A," anyway. A nice change to have a professor that really cares about his students' understanding.
Awful.
he's great in lower level classes, however once concepts get more difficult it's easy to get lost, and you have to do alot of work on your own in order to do well on the exams.
Too nice.
Well meaning professor, knows his field very well; communication skills not up to par - only part of that is that his accent is difficult to understand. Difficult not to do well in his class.
No Comments

Prof Afsar is sometimes difficult to understand, but is always available for extra help. His class usually does better in comparison to the others because the students are better prepared for the tests and know how to apply the material.
No Comments
One of the best professors @ Tufts.  Our class average was 88-90 on each exam, the rest of the grade averaged in the 70's.  The guy is a savage.
At first, you will have no idea what he is talking about. But you will soon understand most of the concepts in the course and you will do really well on the tests.

Not the class if you want an easy "A". You get pushed. You need to be entrepreneurial. There is a lot of freedom and runway to take the class out to the real world. Sherman is a force of nature - super connected, really cares about students. Most rigorous class I had at Tufts by far and the most relevant to getting a job.
horrible professor who uses students
best decision made at tufts, life changing experience.
EPIIC was undeniably the best decision I made at Tufts. Don't try to do all the reading or it will destroy your life. I cannot recommend the course highly enough.
It's been a long time, but I clearly remeber Prof. Teichman as being one the inspiring and devoted educators that I have ever experienced.

Sherman is a force of nature and he cares about inspiring students and expanding their horizons.  EPIIC was, by far, the best college experience that I had and Sherman's energy and emphasis on thinking more than you ever imagined you could made it an unforgettable experience.

don't let that brochure fool you... EPIIC was the absolute worst decision I made at Tufts. Sherman does not care about individuals or whether or not you learn anything. Life to him is one big networking game and you are just a pawn.

Manic, charismatic, deeply affectionate..in EPIIC he created a space in which highly driven students came together & drew from each others' energy to grapple with the BIG ideas & problems. Tufts would have been far less rewarding in his absence. Even the disorg. I think was necessary to create an atmosphere of risk, excitement, growth. Needs holida

EPIIC w/ Sherman and Heather was an experience that I will never forget -- it was extreme in every way, shape, and form, as is Sherman's teaching.  To his credit, he is the hardest-working person I've come across, and his passion for info has no bounds -- inspiring professor w/ concern/compassion for students.
Disorganized, takes advantage of students, needs lots of ego-stroking

Sherman demands an enormous amount from students, and most are rewarded with a valuable interdisciplinary experience.  True - he is eccentric, but his results are undeniable - EPIIC inspires more and better independent research than any other program I experienced at Tufts.
No Comments
conceited, egotistical, narcissistic, dominant, this man made EPIIC a horrible experience. everyone in the class acted as though he was god's gift to Tufts. Sherman's a gigantic phony.

By far the worst "professor" I've ever had.  Totally egotistical, takes all credit for what you've achieved.  Forget expressing independent thought and opinions.  He's a phony...nothing intellectually stimulating about this program.  Wouldn't do
No Comments

Worst prof. at Tufts.  No background on China (on which course is based), horribly disrespectful to students and peers, and completely disorganized.  Not worth taking if interested in learning or going to Hong Kong. Will use and abuse you.

Try to really get to know the man behind the front, the reputation, the booming voice. He may have some wild ideas and he may not always be the easiest person to talk to, but he's genuine. You know what they say; if you can't take the heat...
egomaniacal and annoying to deal with.
The hardest prof you will ever had, but if anyone is the Keymaker, it is him.  But be warned- he has his agenda and only works for you after you have opened the door.
huuuuuuge phony. this guy needs to get down off of his cloud.
No Comments

The Talloires course- he didn't bring up the readings in class, so why should we have done them? The discussions floated all over the place, full of generalizations and imprecise statements that he did nothing to control. He is better as a scholar or academic- he spoke much more clearly about his work than when he "guided" discussions.

It was a great class for Talloires, but he really didn't engage the reading material. It might have been because we had a seminar with a range of disciplines and backgrounds, but there was a lot of potential for in depth discussion and he let the conversations run themselves. A very nice man overall and interesting material for the course.

tests were not bad, if you read the book and attended class especially for guest lectures. the essays however were tricky... he had a very specific idea as to what he wanted our essays to be, but had trouble getting that through to students. so that was unclear. and i can't say that anyone was too happy with his grading system either (for papers).

Hyatt encourages students to discuss and formulate their own responses to the material while introducing key ideas periodically to push the analysis further.  The loose structure seems appropriate for the seminar setting.  Interesting, enjoyable class.
No Comments

This is a discussion class - yet he's terrible at clarifying where his discussion wants to go.  He asks questions that, even if you DO the reading, have no direction, and no clear answers.  Very confusing and unclear.

She's incredibly sweet and cares about students. Loved her as a person, but class was dull and extremely discussion heavy. Once it got going it was better. Her encouragement and feedback when doing our own research were great. Not very organized or clear with grading criteria, though. Easy A, but read the fine print or you're screwed.

His course is quite interesting. I quite enjoy his course and assignment. However, he is a very young lecturer(I think 2019 is his first year to teach). And, I have to say, he lacks teaching experience. The syllabus lacks arrangements. So, the second half-semester is quite busy. But, I think he will become better in the future.

Prof. Bell does not give timely or sufficient feedback on assignments -- at one point, I had submitted over seven assignments that he had yet to grade. One assignment took him over two months to grade. Furthermore, his calculation of the overall course grade was veiled-- I have no way to check his calculation. Overall, frustrating to work for.

Super fun and interesting conversations about cognitive psych! you need to attend lectures and pay attention to all the examples she talks about. she posts the slides but her tests are more on the aspects she delves into during class. textbook readings are helpful and essential for cerego (online study tool that's mandatory).

Prof. Kounaves is a nice dude, but unfortunately the material of the class is very dry. Difficult to stay focused but the most important aspect of the class is lab work and reports, which are heavily weighted in your final grade.

This class almost killed me. Do NOT take this if you haven't taken bio. His tests were the hardest I have ever taken and lectures could be difficult to follow. Down to earth but smarter than you'll ever be. INCREDIBLY interesting subject matter and always willing to discuss things. You'll know the brain inside and out by the end, guaranteed.

Professor Izsak was the best! This was his first time teaching ED130, and he was a fantastic teacher in my opinion. While the material we read throughout the semester was challenging, it truly opened my mind on a lot of topics. Lots of thoughtful group discussions and time spent discussing confusing hw concepts. Highly recommend him as a professor!

Mike is the kind of professor that you would feel lucky if you have one. Workload is high and you learn much from that. He cares students feedbacks. He is inspirational and encouraging. In private, he is nice and friendly. Take BDL with him, and youll never regret.

Genuinely the first bio class I actually enjoyed at Tufts. Most classes IMO are set up for you to fail but Erik would so much rather see his students succeed . Tests are straightforward if you know your stuff so show up to class and take good notes. Material is engaging which makes the course fun!

Erik Dopman is very smart and is an amazing lecturer. He's always very clear and does not throw curveballs on exams. The class is mainly exams but the grading is very fair. Amazing class, highly recommend taking it!

Amazing lectures; interactive; grades by few short exams, reading summaries, and final paper; exams are not hard; lots of extra credits chances; if you are interested in tv, definitely take this class with her.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Get ready to read', 'Clear grading criteria']

rComments: Prof. Martinez is amazing! I learned so much about architecture in just one semester. Her lectures are so in-depth that you don't really need to do readings; however, they may help you better understand course content. Very accessible and grades easily if you pay attention to her expectations for the assignment. Best professor I've had at Tufts!
This is the best class and best professor i have had at Tufts. She is so inspirational, funny, accessible and made me fall in love with architectural history.

Professor Chiesa is great! Had her for ME-0001 and ES-0007. Encourages group work during class to solve problems collaboratively. Encourages you to learn the material to know it, not just for the grade.

Ok so here's the thing about this class, it's stupid easy if you know literally anything about statistics. It moves slower than AP Stats and honestly has so little to do with sociology it kinda hurts. Take it for the math credit, but make sure you have a friend in it with you to wake you up when you inevitably fall asleep. He's super nice though!
Cheryl is sweet and genuinely cares about her students and would like to see them succeed. She is available outside office hours if you have any difficulty in her class.
teacherRatingTags: ['Gives good feedback', 'Accessible outside class', 'Clear grading criteria']

rComments: Luo Laoshi is a very friendly woman. As of this entry, shes still relatively new at teaching and thus still has a bit to go before she can cement her teaching style, but shes open to feedback. Be prepared to practice speaking and listening in her class! Maybe not the most inspirational, but she does want to see you do well.

Bryn is such an amazing woman! She is enthusiastic and caring and she is very smart when it comes to her subject matter. I think her class is a perfect balance of group discussion and essay writing. You always know what is expected of you, and she is flexible with due dates if youre having a tough time. Highly recommend!
Professor Schaffner is a very attentive and smart teacher. He cares about students and is always available to help.

The worst teacher I have come across at Tufts by far. Hes so unclear about grading and expectations, everyone was always unsure of what to do. Hes disorganized, and fixates on really stupid things ex. gets mad when anyone even smiles in class, and bans headphones, talks about irrelevant things so much leaving no time for studio work and alot of hw.
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', 'Lecture heavy', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: The best professor I've had so far. Discussions in class were fascinating! Together the class explored different philosophers' philosophies and with her guidance came to grasp their ideas and concepts. Great at leading discussions! Super helpful with essays! Really nice! Easy grader! Seriously considering a philosophy major after taking her class.
Great class with a great professor. JP genuinely cares about students and is an excellent teacher.

If you are looking for an accessible, non-intense art credit at Tufts, this is THE class to take. Christina Maranci is super chill, but she really cares about the material and knows her stuff. She is extremely knowledgable and realistic; she won't make you do unnecessary work. Two tests, one essay, relatively easy class. Would highly recommend.

Christina Maranci is the Indiana Jones of Armenian Art. She seriously knows her stuff and works hard to make sure all her students succeed. The class is based on 2 tests and an essay. The tests are relatively easy - she gives you all the information that will be on them in the review session. She is the best professor I've taken at Tufts thus far!

Doesn't prepared for out of class meetings (asks for us to send him our paper and specific questions ahead of time, but does not look at it until 5 min before or not at all), in meetings he does't comment on parts of paper that he thinks could be improved upon - instead takes off points after I have turned it in... Has little regard for our stress.

Prof Aeron is great. He teaches a hard class, but the material is interesting. He gives many extra credit opportunities AND he is very accessible in office hours. You can also just go to his OH and talk to him, because he has a lot of ideas about the dept. and he's really good at providing context for the material he teaches. Really knows his stuff
teacherRatingTags: ['Clear grading criteria', 'Gives good feedback', 'Accessible outside class']

rComments: I loved music and ethics. I took the course for an art credit and it ended up being one of my favorite classes at tufts. Professor Latour lets students guide the discussion, which allowed us to bring in more modern topics. The work isn't hard and it is easy to do well. She is great and would definitely recommend the class!

Sort of disorganized and the class wasn't what I think anyone in the class (music majors or WGSS majors) thought it would be. A lot of important topics that weren't touched on at all which surprised. I think half the class got 100% on the midterm. Ultimately, super easy and engaging. Fun class. Lots of discussions

Great prof and class. Sometimes she can be a little out of it when it comes to technology or more modern music, but it's never a huge problem. 99% of the learning occurs through class discussions and she does attendance, so show up. There are a few papers and small assignments, but you can focus on your interests which makes long papers feel easy.

Jivko is possibly the best professor I've had at Tufts. He's done some awesome research and it would be so cool to do research with him. And he's great at explaining stuff and giving lectures - super interesting!

Karen is such a nice lady and a good professor. The topic itself was hard and she did a good job of explaining everything. The grade is mostly based on exams which can be concerning but the lowest one is dropped. Overall, interesting but challenging.
Readings that are online as PDFS, might differ from class lectures, but you should be fine. Only 4 tests during the semester though.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Lecture heavy', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: One of my favorite professors at Tufts so far! I took Phil02 for the English credit, but it ended up being one of the best classes I've taken. Ian is really thoughtful about how he structures the class -- is always open to student input -- and fosters awesome discussions among students. Definitely take a class with him if you can!

Natalie is hands down one of the best parts of my experience at Tufts. As a professor, she caters to each student's style of learning and encourages you to push yourself  be that with respect to effort or experimentation with subject matter. It's about what you learn, not what grade you'll get with her. Definitely a professor worth working with!

Natalie is great at finding the value in everyone's work, as well as giving constructive feedback that's attainable to each individual's level of expertise. She's very passionate about the subject matter and was able to facilitate stimulating conversation that made us think more deeply about documentary work. One of my favorite professors at Tufts.

Mediocre professor. Her lectures are incredibly boring and uninteresting. She's not very ambitious and thus not inspiring. She absolutely WON'T push you to go above and beyond. She's also incredibly strict and unwelcoming when it comes to checking out material at the FMS, thereby limiting your ambitions all the more. Would avoid her at all costs.

Natalie is such an amazing professor! She cares so much about film and media, which makes her feedback thorough, thoughtful, and informed. She is very nice and flexible but definitely not a push-over. Don't try to bs with her because she's super passionate and won't have it; stay on her good side!
best professor in the economics department. wish he taught more classes

Professor Creed-Mendes is very demanding! She encourages her students to apply the material and is a big advocate of hands-on assignments. The class was small, so this made for an intimate learning environment. Overall, Professor Creed-Mendes is very passionate about her subject matter!!
teacherRatingTags: ['Beware of pop quizzes', 'Tough grader', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: Extremely lucky to have taken this course with Professor Hening. He really cares about developing an intuition for the concepts at hand, which really helps you learn the material. Wish we had him for Real 2 this sem.
Prof. Hening gives exceptional lectures. He cares about his students, and always tries to help you on piazza, at office hours or via email. Too bad he will not be teaching Math 136 next semester!

Professor Hening is a VERY nice person, but unfortunately you might only be certain if that after attending office hours. He comes off a bit condescending in class if you have the wrong guess, but in reality I think he means well. Very stylish too.
Very fortunate to have taken the class with Hening. Wish we could have him for Real 2. Highly recommend.

His lectures are extremely clear and he follows Rudin very closely. Exams are reasonable. If you can't make it to his lectures, you can always go to his office hours for help. If you can't go to office hours, then you can get an instant reply on Piazza. Overall a friendly and understanding guy. Highly recommend taking the course with him!

Great material, just a lot of work. There are take-home exams once a month which you have to answer two questions out of about 4. You have to include readings and class material, so make sure you read! It's great that all reading materials are on Jumbosearch. Lots of writing and unnecessary projects. It got tedious and repetitive after a while.
teacherRatingTags: ['So many papers', 'Get ready to read', 'Participation matters']

rComments: Christopher Conz is knowledgable and passionate in his field. I had a great experience in his WR 120 class, as he challenged me to become a better writer and a better academic. He is a bit abrasive at times, but he will be an ally in your career if you are on his good side.
Knows a lot, but not a good teacher. Not great at explaining things. His tests come out of nowhere.

Super nice guy. Completely lacks the condescending demeanor that plagues a lot of STEM professors at Tufts. The material was pretty interesting. It's worth noting that the homeworks are about 50% 50% split between coding and math but the tests are basically straight math

DB is a funny lecturer and does his best to make the material very entertaining. Experimental psych has two group projects/papers and one individual paper. Both require lots of dedicated time and effort, but it is not hard at all. You don't have to attend lecture but would recommend. Just put in some effort, don't stress & it's an easy A!
Easy A

Psych stats with Professor Barch is the easiest of any of the statistics classes you can take at Tufts. Professor Barch is also approachable, caring, and overall great guy. Every quiz and test is open note. Contrary to what many professors think, doing this makes students want to learn bc there's little pressure to memorize and cram :)
Daniel is an absolute gem. Believe it or not, you get to learn the material and get an A at the same time... gotta love him

Professor Barch is one of the easiest teachers I have ever had. He posts the lecture slides online so you only really need to go to class to turn in your homework. You can use your notes, worksheets, and book on the quizzes and exams. I would take this class a million times over again.
